# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: northwestern-university
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:northwestern-university/1949-rose-bowl] The **1949 Rose Bowl** was the 35th edition of the college football bowl game, played at the Rose Bowl in Pasadena, California, on Saturday, January 1.
[src:northwestern-university/1949-rose-bowl] The seventh-ranked Northwestern Wildcats of the Big Nine Conference defeated the #4 California Golden Bears, champions of the Pacific Coast Conference, 20–14.
[src:northwestern-university/1949-rose-bowl] Northwestern halfback Frank Aschenbrenner was named the Player of the Game when the award was created in 1953 and selections were made retroactively.
[src:northwestern-university/1949-rose-bowl] It was the third Rose Bowl since the Big Nine and PCC made an exclusive agreement to match their conference champions; the Big Nine team won for the third straight year.
[src:northwestern-university/1949-rose-bowl] Northwestern has played in just one Rose Bowl since, 47 years later in January 1996.
[src:northwestern-university/1949-rose-bowl] Until the 2013 Gator Bowl, this was the program's only bowl game win.
[src:northwestern-university/1949-rose-bowl] Northwestern had finished 8–2 in the Big 9 Conference, losing only to perennial powerhouses Michigan (0–28) and Notre Dame (7–12).
[src:northwestern-university/1949-rose-bowl] Northwestern blanked UCLA 19–0, Purdue 21–0, and Syracuse 48–0.
[src:northwestern-university/1949-rose-bowl] Northwestern rallied from three turnovers and a 16-point deficit to defeat Minnesota 19–16 as well as defeating Ohio State 21–7, Wisconsin 16–7, and Illinois 20–7.
[src:northwestern-university/1949-rose-bowl] The Big Nine's "no repeat" rule prevented two-time champion Michigan from making a consecutive trip to the Rose Bowl, so second-place Northwestern received the invitation to the game.
[src:northwestern-university/1949-rose-bowl] California had a perfect record going into the game and had averaged 28 points per game over the course of the season.
[src:northwestern-university/1949-rose-bowl] Although neither team had faced each other before, Coach Waldorf had previously been the Wildcats coach from 1935 to 1946 before leaving for the Golden Bears.
[src:northwestern-university/1949-rose-bowl] Northwestern head coach Bob Voigts was only 33-years-old and had been named an All-American in 1938 playing for Waldorf.
[src:northwestern-university/1949-rose-bowl] California and Oregon both had perfect records in the Pacific Coast Conference.
[src:northwestern-university/1949-rose-bowl] California was undefeated overall, and Oregon's only loss was at undefeated Michigan, that year's national champions, and the Ducks had seven victories in the PCC to Cal's six.
[src:northwestern-university/1949-rose-bowl] Oregon, led by quarterback Norm Van Brocklin and halfback John McKay, opted for a playoff game, but California declined.
[src:northwestern-university/1949-rose-bowl] The tiebreaker format the PCC elected to use was that the championship team be elected by the schools.
[src:northwestern-university/1949-rose-bowl] The PCC had ten members in 1948, six in the Northwest and four in California, so it was assumed that Oregon would be the team playing in the Rose Bowl, as even a 5–5 tie vote would be in their favor.
[src:northwestern-university/1949-rose-bowl] Instead California was voted champion of the PCC, because the University of Washington had persuaded the University of Montana, then a member of the PCC, to vote for California, something that has not been forgotten by Oregon fans.
[src:northwestern-university/1949-rose-bowl] Frank Aschenbrenner ran 73 yards, the longest touchdown run in Rose Bowl history.
[src:northwestern-university/1949-rose-bowl] In the second quarter, the Wildcats were awarded a touchdown in a controversial call when Art Murakowski fumbled the ball entering the endzone, but missed the point-after.
[src:northwestern-university/1949-rose-bowl] Although Jensen is injured early in the third quarter, Cal mounted a 56-yard drive for a touchdown and point-after giving them a one-point lead.
[src:northwestern-university/1949-rose-bowl] The Bears attempted a passing drive in the last minute, but PeeWee Day intercepted a pass to end Cal's hopes of a title.
[src:northwestern-university/1949-rose-bowl] Both Aschenbrenner's and Jensen's runs were from scrimmage.
[src:northwestern-university/1949-rose-bowl] The final touchdown was a direct snap from center to a running back (Tunnicliff) from a T-formation set.
[src:northwestern-university/1996-rose-bowl] The **1996 Rose Bowl** was the 82nd Rose Bowl Game.
[src:northwestern-university/1996-rose-bowl] It was the 50th game in the series featuring the Big Ten Conference and the Pacific-10 Conference.
[src:northwestern-university/1996-rose-bowl] The USC Trojans defeated the Northwestern Wildcats, 41–32, on the strength of two touchdown passes from USC quarterback Brad Otton to wide receiver Keyshawn Johnson.
[src:northwestern-university/1996-rose-bowl] Johnson was named the Rose Bowl Player Of The Game.
[src:northwestern-university/1996-rose-bowl] The game was presided over by the 1996 Tournament of Roses Royal Court and Rose Parade Grand Marshal Kermit the Frog.
[src:northwestern-university/1996-rose-bowl] The Northwestern Wildcats had a string of losing seasons stretching back to 1972, and had not appeared in the Rose Bowl for 47 years, a win in January 1949.
[src:northwestern-university/1996-rose-bowl] The Wildcats opened the 1995 season with a surprise 17–15 win at #9 Notre Dame on September 3, 1995.
[src:northwestern-university/1996-rose-bowl] That Notre Dame finished at number 6 and went to the Orange Bowl.
[src:northwestern-university/1996-rose-bowl] However, Notre Dame set the record for largest drop in the rankings AP Poll in the Top-25 era when the next AP poll was released, dropping 16 spots to #25 (this record was beaten by Michigan after losing to Appalachian State during the first week of the 2007 season).
[src:northwestern-university/1996-rose-bowl] The Wildcats, who were then ranked in the AP poll for the first time since 1971, fell out of the spotlight when they lost to Miami University in their next game.
[src:northwestern-university/1996-rose-bowl] They won against Air Force and Indiana to get back to #25 in the polls.
[src:northwestern-university/1996-rose-bowl] On October 2, the Wildcats had another win that brought them back into national attention, a 19–13 victory over Michigan in Ann Arbor.
[src:northwestern-university/1996-rose-bowl] The Wildcats won the rest of their games with a perfect 8–0 record in the Big Ten Conference.
[src:northwestern-university/1996-rose-bowl] The USC Trojans opened with six wins until losing at Notre Dame, 38–10, on October 21.
[src:northwestern-university/1996-rose-bowl] On October 28, USC and Washington played what would be the deciding game for the conference at Husky Stadium.
[src:northwestern-university/1996-rose-bowl] Down 21–0 in the fourth quarter, the Trojans scored three straight touchdowns, with the final coming with 33 seconds remaining.
[src:northwestern-university/1996-rose-bowl] A Washington loss to Oregon on November 4 put USC in the lead in the Pac-10 race.
[src:northwestern-university/1996-rose-bowl] Coming into the UCLA–USC rivalry game, the Trojans already had the Rose Bowl berth by virtue of more non-conference victories than Washington, even though a loss to the Bruins would leave both teams with a 6–1–1 record.
[src:northwestern-university/2013-gator-bowl] The **2013 TaxSlayer.com Gator Bowl** was a post-season American college football bowl game held on January 1, 2013, at EverBank Field in Jacksonville, Florida in the United States.
[src:northwestern-university/2013-gator-bowl] The 68th edition of the Gator Bowl began at noon EST and aired on ESPN2.
[src:northwestern-university/2013-gator-bowl] It featured the Mississippi State Bulldogs from the Southeastern Conference (SEC) against the Northwestern Wildcats from the Big Ten Conference and was the final game of the 2012 NCAA Division I FBS football season for both teams.
[src:northwestern-university/2013-gator-bowl] The Bulldogs accepted their bowl bid after an 8–4 regular season, while the Wildcats accepted theirs after a 9–3 finish.
[src:northwestern-university/2013-gator-bowl] It was the first time that the two teams had met.
[src:northwestern-university/2013-gator-bowl] Northwestern won the game by a score of 34 – 20.
[src:northwestern-university/2013-gator-bowl] With a 3–0 start in conference play (and a 7–0 start overall), the season had a bright outlook for the Bulldogs.
[src:northwestern-university/2013-gator-bowl] However, the schedule's increasing difficulty put the Bulldogs in decline, only finishing at 4–4 and fourth place in the SEC Western Division.
[src:northwestern-university/2013-gator-bowl] This was the Bulldogs' second Gator Bowl; they had previously played in the 2011 game, soundly defeating the Michigan Wolverines by a score of 52–14.
[src:northwestern-university/2013-gator-bowl] The Wildcats were undefeated out of conference and posted a 5–3 Big Ten record, good for third place in the Legends Division.
[src:northwestern-university/2013-gator-bowl] Only a one-point loss to the Nebraska Cornhuskers and an overtime loss to the Michigan Wolverines kept the Wildcats from the division title and a trip to the conference championship game.
[src:northwestern-university/2013-gator-bowl] This game was the Wildcats' first Gator Bowl; it was also their unprecedented fifth consecutive bowl game.
[src:northwestern-university/2013-gator-bowl] The Wildcats got their first bowl victory since the 1948 team won the 1949 Rose Bowl over the California Golden Bears by a score of 20–14.
[src:northwestern-university/a-cappella] Music performed **a cappella** (/ˌɑː kəˈpɛlə/ *AH kə-PEL-ə*, UK also /ˌæ kəˈpɛlə/ *AK ə-PEL-ə*; Italian: [a kkapˈpɛlla]; lit.
[src:northwestern-university/a-cappella] 'in [the style of] the chapel'), less commonly spelled **a capella** in English, is music performed by a singer or a singing group without instrumental accompaniment.
[src:northwestern-university/a-cappella] The term *a cappella* was originally intended to differentiate between Renaissance polyphonic and Baroque *concertato* musical styles.
[src:northwestern-university/a-cappella] In the 19th century, a renewed interest in Renaissance polyphony, coupled with an ignorance of the fact that vocal parts were often doubled by instrumentalists, led to the term coming to mean unaccompanied vocal music.
[src:northwestern-university/a-cappella] The term is also used, rarely, as a synonym for *alla breve*.
[src:northwestern-university/a-cappella] Research suggests that singing and vocables may have been what early humans used to communicate before the invention of language.
[src:northwestern-university/a-cappella] The earliest instructions for performing music were found on a cuneiform tablet from around 2000 BC, while the earliest that has survived in its entirety is from the first century AD: a piece from Greece called the Seikilos epitaph.
[src:northwestern-university/a-cappella] A cappella music was originally used in religious music, especially church music as well as anasheed and zemirot.
[src:northwestern-university/a-cappella] Gregorian chant is an example of a cappella singing, as is the majority of secular vocal music from the Renaissance.
[src:northwestern-university/a-cappella] The madrigal, up until its development in the early Baroque into an instrumentally accompanied form, was also usually performed a cappella.
[src:northwestern-university/a-cappella] Jewish and Early Christian music was largely a cappella, though instrument use subsequently increased in both religions as well as in Islam.
[src:northwestern-university/a-cappella] The early a cappella polyphonies were sometimes doubled with other instruments, which were often wind or string instruments, or organs.
[src:northwestern-university/a-cappella] By the 16th century, a cappella polyphony had further developed, but gradually, the cantata began to take the place of a cappella forms.
[src:northwestern-university/a-cappella] Sixteenth-century a cappella polyphony, nonetheless, continued to influence church composers throughout this period and to the present day.
[src:northwestern-university/a-cappella] Recent evidence has shown that some of the early pieces by Palestrina, such as those written for the Sistine Chapel, were intended to be accompanied by an organ "doubling" for some or all of the voices.
[src:northwestern-university/a-cappella] Five of Schutz's *Historien* were Easter pieces, and of these the latter three, which dealt with the passion from three different viewpoints, those of Matthew, Luke and John, were all done a cappella style.
[src:northwestern-university/a-cappella] The parts of the crowd were sung while the solo parts which were the quoted parts from either Christ or the authors were performed in a plainchant.
[src:northwestern-university/a-cappella] In the Byzantine Rite of the Eastern Orthodox Church, Eastern Lutheran Churches and the Eastern Catholic Churches, the music performed in the liturgies is exclusively sung without instrumental accompaniment.
[src:northwestern-university/a-cappella] Early Russian *musika* which started appearing in the late 17th century, in what was known as *khorovïye kontsertï* (choral concertos) made a cappella adaptations of Venetian-styled pieces, such as the treatise, *Grammatika musikiyskaya* (1675), by Nikolai Diletsky.
[src:northwestern-university/a-cappella] Divine Liturgies and Western Rite Masses composed by famous composers such as Peter Tchaikovsky, Sergei Rachmaninoff, Alexander Arkhangelsky, and Mykola Leontovych are examples.
[src:northwestern-university/a-cappella] Instruments have divided Christendom since their introduction into worship.
[src:northwestern-university/a-cappella] They were considered a Roman Catholic innovation, not widely practiced until the 18th century, and were opposed vigorously in worship by a number of Protestant Reformers, including Martin Luther, Ulrich Zwingli, John Calvin, and John Wesley.
[src:northwestern-university/a-cappella] Opponents of musical instruments in the Christian worship believe that such opposition is supported by the Christian scriptures and Church history.
[src:northwestern-university/a-cappella] There is no reference to instrumental music in early church worship in the New Testament, or in the worship of churches for the first six centuries.
[src:northwestern-university/a-cappella] Several reasons have been posited throughout church history for the absence of instrumental music in church worship.
[src:northwestern-university/a-cappella] Those who do not adhere to the regulative principle of interpreting Christian scripture, believe that limiting praise to the unaccompanied chant of the early church is not commanded in scripture, and that churches in any age are free to offer their songs with or without musical instruments.
[src:northwestern-university/a-cappella] Those who subscribe to this interpretation believe that since the Christian scriptures never counter instrumental language with any negative judgment on instruments, opposition to instruments instead comes from an interpretation of history.
[src:northwestern-university/a-cappella] There is no written opposition to musical instruments in any setting in the first century and a half of Christian churches (33–180 AD).
[src:northwestern-university/a-cappella] The use of instruments for Christian worship during this period is also undocumented.
[src:northwestern-university/a-cappella] Toward the end of the 2nd century, Christians began condemning the instruments themselves.
[src:northwestern-university/a-cappella] Those who oppose instruments today believe these Church Fathers had a better understanding of God's desire for the church, but there are significant differences between the teachings of these Church Fathers and Christian opposition to instruments today.
[src:northwestern-university/a-cappella] Modern Christians typically believe it is acceptable to play instruments or to attend weddings, funerals, banquets, etc., where instruments are heard playing religious music.
[src:northwestern-university/a-cappella] Since "a cappella" singing brought a new polyphony (more than one note at a time) with instrumental accompaniment, it is not surprising that Protestant reformers who opposed the instruments (such as Calvin and Zwingli) also opposed the polyphony.
[src:northwestern-university/a-cappella] While Zwingli was destroying organs in Switzerland – Luther called him a fanatic – the Church of England was burning books of polyphony.
[src:northwestern-university/a-cappella] Some Holiness Churches such as the Free Methodist Church opposed the use of musical instruments in church worship until the mid-20th century.
[src:northwestern-university/a-cappella] The Free Methodist Church allowed for local church decision on the use of either an organ or piano in the 1943 Conference before lifting the ban entirely in 1955.
[src:northwestern-university/a-cappella] The Reformed Free Methodist Church and Evangelical Wesleyan Church were formed as a result of a schism with the Free Methodist Church, with the former retaining a cappella worship and the latter retaining the rule limiting the number of instruments in the church to the piano and organ.
[src:northwestern-university/a-cappella] Certain high church services and other musical events in liturgical churches (such as the Roman Catholic Mass and the Lutheran Divine Service) may be a cappella, a practice remaining from apostolic times.
[src:northwestern-university/a-cappella] Many Mennonites also conduct some or all of their services without instruments.
[src:northwestern-university/a-cappella] Sacred Harp, a type of folk music, is an a cappella style of religious singing with shape notes, usually sung at singing conventions.
[src:northwestern-university/a-cappella] Traditional Jewish religious services did not include musical instruments given the practice of scriptural cantillation.
[src:northwestern-university/a-cappella] The use of musical instruments is traditionally forbidden on the Sabbath out of concern that players would be tempted to repair (or tune) their instruments, which is forbidden on those days.
[src:northwestern-university/a-cappella] During the Three Weeks musical instruments are prohibited.
[src:northwestern-university/a-cappella] Many Jews consider a portion of the 49-day period of the counting of the omer between Passover and Shavuot to be a time of semi-mourning and instrumental music is not allowed during that time.
[src:northwestern-university/a-cappella] This has led to a tradition of a cappella singing sometimes known as *sefirah* music.
[src:northwestern-university/a-cappella] The popularization of the Jewish chant may be found in the writings of the Jewish philosopher Philo, born 20 BC.
[src:northwestern-university/a-cappella] Weaving together Jewish and Greek thought, Philo promoted praise without instruments, and taught that "silent singing" (without even vocal chords) was better still.
[src:northwestern-university/a-cappella] The shofar is the only temple instrument still being used today in the synagogue, and it is only used from Rosh Chodesh Elul through the end of Yom Kippur.
[src:northwestern-university/a-cappella] The shofar is used by itself, without any vocal accompaniment, and is limited to a very strictly defined set of sounds and specific places in the synagogue service.
[src:northwestern-university/a-cappella] Peter Christian Lutkin, dean of the Northwestern University School of Music, helped popularize a cappella music in the United States by founding the Northwestern A Cappella Choir in 1906.
[src:northwestern-university/a-cappella] An a cappella tradition was begun in 1911 by F.
[src:northwestern-university/a-cappella] Melius Christiansen, a music faculty member at St.
[src:northwestern-university/a-cappella] Olaf College Choir was established as an outgrowth of the local St.
[src:northwestern-university/a-cappella] John's Lutheran Church, where Christiansen was organist and the choir was composed, at least partially, of students from the nearby St.
[src:northwestern-university/a-cappella] Peter, Minnesota), Augustana College (Sioux Falls, South Dakota), and Augsburg University (Minneapolis, Minnesota).
[src:northwestern-university/a-cappella] The choirs typically range from 40 to 80 singers and are recognized for their efforts to perfect blend, intonation, phrasing and pitch in a large choral setting.
[src:northwestern-university/a-cappella] Movements in modern a cappella over the past century include barbershop and doo-wop.
[src:northwestern-university/a-cappella] Many a cappella groups can be found in high schools and colleges.
[src:northwestern-university/a-cappella] There are amateur Barbershop Harmony Society and professional groups that sing a cappella exclusively.
[src:northwestern-university/a-cappella] Although a cappella is technically defined as singing without instrumental accompaniment, some groups use their voices to emulate instruments; others are more traditional and focus on harmonizing.
[src:northwestern-university/a-cappella] A cappella styles range from gospel music to contemporary to barbershop quartets and choruses.
[src:northwestern-university/a-cappella] The Contemporary A Cappella Society (CASA) is a membership option for former students, whose funds support hosted competitions and events.
[src:northwestern-university/a-cappella] A cappella music was popularized between the late 2000s and the early to mid-2010s with media hits such as the 2009–2014 TV show *The Sing-Off* and the musical comedy film series *Pitch Perfect*.
[src:northwestern-university/a-cappella] In July 1943, as a result of the American Federation of Musicians boycott of US recording studios, the a cappella vocal group *The Song Spinners* had a best-seller with "Comin' In on a Wing and a Prayer".
[src:northwestern-university/a-cappella] In the 1950s, several recording groups, notably The Hi-Los and the Four Freshmen, introduced complex jazz harmonies to a cappella performances.
[src:northwestern-university/a-cappella] The King's Singers are credited with promoting interest in small-group a cappella performances in the 1960s.
[src:northwestern-university/a-cappella] Frank Zappa loved doo wop and a cappella, so Zappa released The Persuasions' first album from his label in 1970.
[src:northwestern-university/a-cappella] Judy Collins recorded "Amazing Grace" a cappella.
[src:northwestern-university/a-cappella] In 1983, an a cappella group known as The Flying Pickets had a Christmas 'number one' in the UK with a cover of Yazoo's (known in the US as Yaz) "Only You".
[src:northwestern-university/a-cappella] A cappella music attained renewed prominence from the late 1980s onward, spurred by the success of Top 40 recordings by artists such as The Manhattan Transfer, Bobby McFerrin, Huey Lewis and the News, All-4-One, The Nylons, Backstreet Boys, Boyz II Men, and *NSYNC.
[src:northwestern-university/a-cappella] Contemporary a cappella includes many vocal groups and bands who add vocal percussion or beatboxing to create a pop/rock/gospel sound, in some cases very similar to bands with instruments.
[src:northwestern-university/a-cappella] Examples of such professional groups include Straight No Chaser, Pentatonix, The House Jacks, Rockapella, Mosaic, Home Free, M-pact, and VoicePlay.
[src:northwestern-university/a-cappella] There also remains a strong a cappella presence within Christian music, as some denominations purposefully do not use instruments during worship.
[src:northwestern-university/a-cappella] Examples of such groups are Take 6, Glad and Acappella.
[src:northwestern-university/a-cappella] Arrangements of popular music for small a cappella ensembles typically include one voice singing the lead melody, one singing a rhythmic bass line, and the remaining voices contributing chordal or polyphonic accompaniment.
[src:northwestern-university/a-cappella] A cappella can also describe the isolated vocal track(s) from a multitrack recording that originally included instrumentation.
[src:northwestern-university/a-cappella] These vocal tracks may be remixed or put onto vinyl records for DJs, or released to the public so that fans can remix them.
[src:northwestern-university/a-cappella] One such example is the a cappella release of Jay-Z's *Black Album*, which Danger Mouse mixed with the Beatles' *White Album* to create *The Grey Album*.
[src:northwestern-university/a-cappella] On their 1966 album titled *Album*, Peter, Paul and Mary included the song "Norman Normal".
[src:northwestern-university/a-cappella] All the sounds on that song, both vocals and instruments, were created by Paul's voice, with no actual instruments used.
[src:northwestern-university/a-cappella] In 2013, an artist by the name Smooth McGroove rose to prominence with his style of a cappella music.
[src:northwestern-university/a-cappella] He is best known for his a cappella covers of video game music tracks on YouTube.
[src:northwestern-university/a-cappella] in 2015, an a cappella version of Jerusalem by multi-instrumentalist Jacob Collier was selected for Beats by Dre "The Game Starts Here" for the England Rugby World Cup campaign.
[src:northwestern-university/a-cappella] A cappella has been used as the sole orchestration for original works of musical theatre that have had commercial runs Off-Broadway (theatres in New York City with 99 to 500 seats) only four times.
[src:northwestern-university/a-cappella] The first was *Avenue X* which opened on 28 January 1994, and ran for 77 performances.
[src:northwestern-university/a-cappella] It was produced by Playwrights Horizons with book by John Jiler, music and lyrics by Ray Leslee.
[src:northwestern-university/a-cappella] The musical style of the show's score was primarily doo-wop as the plot revolved around doo-wop group singers of the 1960s.
[src:northwestern-university/a-cappella] In 2001, The Kinsey Sicks, produced and starred in the critically acclaimed off-Broadway hit, *DRAGAPELLA!
[src:northwestern-university/a-cappella] Starring the Kinsey Sicks* at New York's Studio 54.
[src:northwestern-university/a-cappella] That production received a nomination for a Lucille Lortel award as Best Musical and a Drama Desk nomination for Best Lyrics.
[src:northwestern-university/a-cappella] It was directed by Glenn Casale with original music and lyrics by Ben Schatz.
[src:northwestern-university/a-cappella] The fourth a cappella musical to appear Off-Broadway, *In Transit*, premiered October 5, 2010, and was produced by Primary Stages with book, music, and lyrics by Kristen Anderson-Lopez, James-Allen Ford, Russ Kaplan, and Sara Wordsworth.
[src:northwestern-university/a-cappella] Set primarily in the New York City subway system its score features an eclectic mix of musical genres (including jazz, hip hop, Latin, rock, and country).
[src:northwestern-university/a-cappella] In Transit incorporates vocal beat boxing into its contemporary a cappella arrangements through the use of a subway beat boxer character.
[src:northwestern-university/a-cappella] Beat boxer and actor Chesney Snow performed this role for the 2010 Primary Stages production.
[src:northwestern-university/a-cappella] According to the show's website, it is scheduled to reopen for an open-ended commercial run in the Fall of 2011.
[src:northwestern-university/a-cappella] In 2011, the production received four Lucille Lortel Award nominations including Outstanding Musical, Outer Critics Circle and Drama League nominations, as well as five Drama Desk nominations including Outstanding Musical and won for Outstanding Ensemble Performance.
[src:northwestern-university/a-cappella] In December 2016, *In Transit* became the first a cappella musical on Broadway.
[src:northwestern-university/a-cappella] Barbershop music is one of several uniquely American art forms that involve cappella music as well as African American singers.
[src:northwestern-university/a-cappella] The earliest documented quartets all began in barber shops.
[src:northwestern-university/a-cappella] In 1938, the first formal men's barbershop organization was formed, known as the Society for the Preservation and Encouragement of Barber Shop Quartet Singing in America (S.P.E.B.S.Q.S.A), and in 2004 rebranded itself and officially changed its public name to the Barbershop Harmony Society (BHS).
[src:northwestern-university/a-cappella] Today, BHS has about 22,000 members in approximately 800 chapters across the United States and Canada, and the barbershop style has spread around the world with organizations in many other countries.
[src:northwestern-university/a-cappella] The Barbershop Harmony Society provides a highly organized competition structure for a cappella quartets and choruses singing in the barbershop style.
[src:northwestern-university/a-cappella] In 1945, the first formal women's barbershop organization, Sweet Adelines, was formed.
[src:northwestern-university/a-cappella] In 1953, Sweet Adelines became an international organization, although it did not change its name to Sweet Adelines International until 1991 and subsequently changed its name to SingUnited International in 2026.
[src:northwestern-university/a-cappella] The membership of nearly 25,000 women, all singing in English, includes choruses in most of the fifty United States as well as in Australia, Canada, Finland, Germany, Ireland, Japan, New Zealand, Spain, Sweden, the United Kingdom, and the Netherlands.
[src:northwestern-university/a-cappella] Headquartered in Tulsa, Oklahoma, the organization encompasses more than 1,200 registered quartets and 600 choruses.
[src:northwestern-university/a-cappella] In 1959, a second women's barbershop organization started.
[src:northwestern-university/a-cappella] Based on democratic principles which continue to this day, Harmony, Incorporated is smaller than its counterpart, but has an atmosphere of friendship and competition.
[src:northwestern-university/a-cappella] With over 2,000 members in the United States and Canada, Harmony, Inc. uses the same rules in contest that the Barbershop Harmony Society uses.
[src:northwestern-university/a-cappella] High school groups may have conductors or student leaders who keep the tempo for the group, or beatboxers/vocal percussionists.
[src:northwestern-university/a-cappella] Since 2013, summer training programs have appeared, such as A Cappella Academy in Los Angeles, California (founded by Ben Bram, Rob Dietz, and Avi Kaplan) and Camp A Cappella in Dayton, Ohio (founded by Deke Sharon and Brody McDonald).
[src:northwestern-university/a-cappella] These programs teach about different aspects of a cappella music, including vocal performance, arranging, and beatboxing/vocal percussion.
[src:northwestern-university/a-cappella] The Rensselyrics of Rensselaer Polytechnic Institute (formerly known as the RPI Glee Club), established in 1873 is perhaps the oldest known collegiate a cappella group.
[src:northwestern-university/a-cappella] The longest continuously singing group is likely The Whiffenpoofs of Yale University, which formed in 1909 and once included Cole Porter as a member.
[src:northwestern-university/a-cappella] Collegiate a cappella groups grew throughout the 20th century.
[src:northwestern-university/a-cappella] All-women a cappella groups followed shortly, with names frequently parodying men's groups: the Smiffenpoofs of Smith College (1936), the Night Owls of Vassar College (1942), The Shwiffs of Connecticut College (1944), and The Chattertocks of Brown University (1951).
[src:northwestern-university/a-cappella] A cappella groups exploded in popularity beginning in the 1990s, fueled in part by a change in style popularized by the Tufts University Beelzebubs and the Boston University Dear Abbeys.
[src:northwestern-university/a-cappella] The new style used voices to emulate modern rock instruments, including vocal percussion/"beatboxing".
[src:northwestern-university/a-cappella] Some larger universities now have multiple groups.
[src:northwestern-university/a-cappella] In December 2009, a new television competition series called *The Sing-Off* aired on NBC.
[src:northwestern-university/a-cappella] The show featured eight a cappella groups from the United States and Puerto Rico vying for the prize of $100,000 and a recording contract with Epic Records/Sony Music.
[src:northwestern-university/a-cappella] The show was judged by Ben Folds, Shawn Stockman, and Nicole Scherzinger and was won by an all-male group from Puerto Rico called Nota.
[src:northwestern-university/a-cappella] The show returned for a second, third, fourth, and fifth season, won by Committed, Pentatonix, Home Free, and The Melodores from Vanderbilt University respectively.
[src:northwestern-university/a-cappella] Each year, hundreds of collegiate a cappella groups submit their strongest songs in a competition to be on The Best of College A Cappella (BOCA), an album compilation of tracks from the best college a cappella groups around the world.
[src:northwestern-university/a-cappella] The album is produced by Varsity Vocals ,which also produces the International Championship of Collegiate A Cappella , and Deke Sharon.
[src:northwestern-university/a-cappella] Collegiate a cappella groups also submit their tracks to Voices Only, a two-disc series released annually since 2005.
[src:northwestern-university/a-cappella] From 2014 to 2019, the Women's A Cappella Association (WACA) produced an annual best of women's a cappella album.
[src:northwestern-university/a-cappella] The popularity of a cappella was revived by television shows and movies such as *Glee* and *Pitch Perfect,* with the latter being more a cappella-focused than the former, whose focus lies more on traditional musical theater.
[src:northwestern-university/a-cappella] Since the release of Pitch Perfect in late 2012, the amount of coed a cappella groups has risen far more sharply than in the years prior.
[src:northwestern-university/a-cappella] The Islamic Emirate of Afghanistan has no official anthem because of views by the Taliban of music as un-Islamic.
[src:northwestern-university/a-cappella] However, the *de facto* national anthem of Afghanistan is an a cappella nasheed, as musical instruments are virtually banned as corrupting and un-Islamic.
[src:northwestern-university/a-cappella] Australia saw a rise in a cappella groups during the 1980s and 1990s with groups such as Blindman’s Holiday, Arramaeida, Martenitsa Choir, Cafe at the Gate of Salvation, and the Heavenly Light Quartet.
[src:northwestern-university/a-cappella] Vocal music and community choirs have become popular in most towns and suburbs of Australia since 2010, with regular concerts, events and festivals dedicated solely to vocal music performances.
[src:northwestern-university/a-cappella] The first a cappella group in Iran is the Damour Vocal Band, which was able to perform on national television despite a ban on women singing.
[src:northwestern-university/a-cappella] The musical show *Strepsils Stereo* is credited for introducing the art of a cappella in Pakistan.
[src:northwestern-university/a-cappella] Composer Dinesh Subasinghe became the first Sri Lankan to write a cappella pieces for SATB choirs.
[src:northwestern-university/a-cappella] He wrote "The Princes of the Lost Tribe" and "Ancient Queen of Somawathee" for Menaka De Sahabandu and Bridget Helpe's choirs, respectively, based on historical incidents in ancient Sri Lanka.
[src:northwestern-university/a-cappella] Voice Print is also a professional a cappella music group in Sri Lanka.
[src:northwestern-university/a-cappella] The European a cappella tradition is strong in the countries around the Baltic, including in Sweden as described by Richard Sparks in *The Swedish Choral Miracle* in 2000.
[src:northwestern-university/a-cappella] Swedish a cappella choirs have over the last 25 years won around 25% of the annual prestigious European Grand Prix for Choral Singing (EGP) that despite its name is open to choirs from all over the world (see list of laureates in the Wikipedia article on the EGP competition).
[src:northwestern-university/a-cappella] Sparks explains that in Sweden an unusually large proportion of the populations (5% is often cited) regularly sing in choirs.
[src:northwestern-university/a-cappella] In British universities, there are numerous a capella groups.
[src:northwestern-university/a-cappella] UK a capella organisations include The Voice Festival UK and the integration of the United Kingdom into the International Championship of Collegiate A Cappella.
[src:northwestern-university/a-cappella] South Asian a cappella features a fusion of music from the Indian subcontinent, which places it in the category of South Asian fusion music.
[src:northwestern-university/a-cappella] A cappella is gaining popularity among South Asians with the emergence of primarily Hindi-English college groups.
[src:northwestern-university/a-cappella] The first South Asian a cappella group was Penn Masala, an all-male group founded in 1996 at the University of Pennsylvania.
[src:northwestern-university/a-cappella] The first co-ed South Asian a cappella was Anokha, from the University of Maryland, formed in 2001.
[src:northwestern-university/a-cappella] The first South Asian A Cappella competition was "Anahat," hosted by the Indus student organization at UC Berkeley.
[src:northwestern-university/a-cappella] Maize Mirchi, the co-ed a cappella group from the University of Michigan became the first South Asian group to advance to ICCA finals in 2023.
[src:northwestern-university/a-cappella] The South Asian a cappella competitive circuit is governed by the Association of South-Asian A Cappella (ASA), a non-profit organization formed in 2016.
[src:northwestern-university/a-cappella] The competitive circuit consists of qualifier "bid" competitions all over the United States, as well as the national championship, All-American Awaaz.
[src:northwestern-university/a-cappella] The first winner of the championship title was Swaram A Cappella at Texas A&M University, who won 1st place at All-American Awaaz in 2017 in New York City as well as in 2018 in Chicago.
[src:northwestern-university/a-cappella] Dhamakapella currently holds the record for most All-American Awaaz championships, winning three consecutive championships in 2022, 2023, and 2024.
[src:northwestern-university/a-cappella] In addition to singing words, some a cappella singers also emulate instrumentation by reproducing instrumental sounds with their vocal cords and mouth, often pitched using specialised pitch pipes.
[src:northwestern-university/a-cappella] One of the earliest 20th century practitioners of this method were The Mills Brothers.
[src:northwestern-university/a-cappella] More recently, "Twilight Zone" by 2 Unlimited was sung a cappella to the instrumentation on the comedy television series *Tompkins Square*.
[src:northwestern-university/a-cappella] Another famous example of emulating instrumentation instead of singing the words is the theme song for *The New Addams Family* series on Fox Family Channel (now Freeform).
[src:northwestern-university/a-cappella] Groups such as Vocal Sampling emulate Latin rhythms a cappella.
[src:northwestern-university/a-cappella] In the 1960s, the Swingle Singers used their voices to emulate musical instruments to Baroque and Classical music.
[src:northwestern-university/a-cappella] Vocal artist Bobby McFerrin is famous for his instrumental emulation.
[src:northwestern-university/a-cappella] A cappella group Naturally Seven recreates entire songs using vocal tones for every instrument.
[src:northwestern-university/a-cappella] Beatboxing, more accurately known as vocal percussion, is a technique used in a cappella music popularized by the hip-hop community, where rap is often performed a cappella.
[src:northwestern-university/a-cappella] The advent of vocal percussion has become prevalent in modern arrangements.
[src:northwestern-university/a-song-of-ice-and-fire-p01] The novels are set on the fictional continents of Westeros and Essos (the world as a whole does not have an established name).
[src:northwestern-university/a-song-of-ice-and-fire-p01] Martin's stated inspirations for the series include many supposed historic events.
[src:northwestern-university/a-song-of-ice-and-fire-p01] As of 2026, more than 100 million copies in 47 languages had been sold.
[src:northwestern-university/a-song-of-ice-and-fire-p01] The fourth and fifth volumes reached the top of the *New York Times* Best Seller lists when published in 2005 and 2011 respectively.
[src:northwestern-university/a-song-of-ice-and-fire-p01] Among the many derived works are several prequel novellas, three television series, a comic book adaptation, and several card, board, and video games.
[src:northwestern-university/a-song-of-ice-and-fire-p01] The series has received critical acclaim for its world-building, characters, and narrative.
[src:northwestern-university/a-song-of-ice-and-fire-p01] The principal story chronicles the power struggle for the Iron Throne among the great Houses of Westeros following the death of King Robert in *A Game of Thrones*.
[src:northwestern-university/a-song-of-ice-and-fire-p01] Robert's heir apparent, the 13-year-old Joffrey, is immediately proclaimed king through the machinations of his mother, Queen Cersei Lannister.
[src:northwestern-university/a-song-of-ice-and-fire-p01] When Lord Eddard "Ned" Stark — Robert's closest friend and chief advisor — discovers that Joffrey and his siblings are the product of incest between Cersei and her twin brother Ser Jaime Lannister, Eddard attempts to unseat Joffrey, but is betrayed and executed for treason.
[src:northwestern-university/a-song-of-ice-and-fire-p01] In response, Robert's younger brothers Stannis and Renly lay separate claims to the throne.
[src:northwestern-university/a-song-of-ice-and-fire-p01] During this period of instability, two of the Seven Kingdoms of Westeros attempt to become independent from the Iron Throne: Eddard's eldest son Robb is proclaimed King in the North, while Lord Balon Greyjoy desires to recover the independence of his kingdom, the Iron Islands.
[src:northwestern-university/a-song-of-ice-and-fire-p01] The so-called "War of the Five Kings" is in full progress by the middle of the second book, *A Clash of Kings*.
[src:northwestern-university/a-song-of-ice-and-fire-p01] This story is told principally through the perspectives of Eddard's wife Catelyn, their children Sansa, Arya, and Bran, and Jaime and Cersei's younger brother Tyrion Lannister, with more point-of-view characters added as the novels continue.
[src:northwestern-university/a-song-of-ice-and-fire-p01] The second storyline stems from the far north of Westeros, where an 8,000-year-old wall of ice, simply called "the Wall", defends the Seven Kingdoms from supernatural creatures known as the Others.
[src:northwestern-university/a-song-of-ice-and-fire-p01] The Wall's sentinels, the Sworn Brotherhood of the Night's Watch, also protect the realm from incursions by the "wildlings" or "Free Folk", a number of human tribes living on the north side of the Wall.
[src:northwestern-university/a-song-of-ice-and-fire-p01] The story of The Night's Watch is told primarily through the point of view of Jon Snow, Lord Eddard Stark's bastard son.
[src:northwestern-university/a-song-of-ice-and-fire-p01] Jon follows in the footsteps of his paternal uncle Benjen Stark and joins the Watch at a young age, rising quickly through the ranks.
[src:northwestern-university/a-song-of-ice-and-fire-p01] He eventually becomes Lord Commander of the Night's Watch.
[src:northwestern-university/a-song-of-ice-and-fire-p01] In the third volume, *A Storm of Swords*, the Night's Watch storyline becomes increasingly entangled with the War of the Five Kings when King Stannis Baratheon arrives at the Wall.
[src:northwestern-university/a-song-of-ice-and-fire-p01] The third storyline follows Daenerys Targaryen, daughter of Aerys II.
[src:northwestern-university/a-song-of-ice-and-fire-p01] On the continent of Essos, east of Westeros across the Narrow Sea, Daenerys is married off by her elder brother Viserys to a powerful warlord of the nomadic Dothraki.
[src:northwestern-university/a-song-of-ice-and-fire-p01] Over the course of her story, Daenerys slowly becomes an independent and intelligent ruler in her own right.
[src:northwestern-university/a-song-of-ice-and-fire-p01] Her rise to power is aided by the historic birth of three dragons, hatched from eggs given to her as wedding gifts.
[src:northwestern-university/a-song-of-ice-and-fire-p01] The three dragons soon become not only a symbol of her bloodline and her claim to the throne but also devastating weapons of war, which help her in the conquest of Slaver's Bay.
[src:northwestern-university/a-song-of-ice-and-fire-p01] The later books follow her ongoing conflict with the region's city-states, in which she aims to consolidate power, disrupt the Essosi slave trade, and gather support for her ambitions to reclaim Westeros.
[src:northwestern-university/a-song-of-ice-and-fire-p01] Books in the *A Song of Ice and Fire* series are first published in hardcover and are later re-released as paperback editions.
[src:northwestern-university/a-song-of-ice-and-fire-p01] In the UK, Harper Voyager publishes special slipcased editions.
[src:northwestern-university/a-song-of-ice-and-fire-p01] The series has also been translated into more than 30 languages.
[src:northwestern-university/a-song-of-ice-and-fire-p01] All page totals given below are for the US first editions.
[src:northwestern-university/a-song-of-ice-and-fire-p01] Martin was already a successful fantasy and sci-fi author and TV writer before writing his *A Song of Ice and Fire* book series.
[src:northwestern-university/a-song-of-ice-and-fire-p01] Martin had his first short story published in 1971 and his first novel in 1977.
[src:northwestern-university/a-song-of-ice-and-fire-p01] By the mid-1990s, he had won three Hugo Awards, two Nebula Awards, and other awards for his short fiction.
[src:northwestern-university/a-song-of-ice-and-fire-p01] Although his early books were well-received within the fantasy fiction community, his readership remained relatively small and Martin took on jobs as a writer in Hollywood in the mid-1980s.
[src:northwestern-university/a-song-of-ice-and-fire-p01] He worked principally on the revival of *The Twilight Zone* throughout 1986 and on *Beauty and the Beast* until 1990, but he also developed his own TV pilots and wrote feature film scripts.
[src:northwestern-university/a-song-of-ice-and-fire-p01] He grew frustrated that his pilots and screenplays were not getting made and that TV-related production limitations like budgets and episode lengths were forcing him to cut characters and trim battle scenes.
[src:northwestern-university/a-song-of-ice-and-fire-p01] This pushed Martin back towards writing books, where he did not have to worry about compromising the size of his imagination.
[src:northwestern-university/a-song-of-ice-and-fire-p01] Tolkien in his childhood, he wanted to write an epic fantasy, though he did not have any specific ideas.
[src:northwestern-university/a-song-of-ice-and-fire-p01] When Martin was between Hollywood projects in the summer of 1991, he started writing a new science fiction novel called *Avalon*.
[src:northwestern-university/a-song-of-ice-and-fire-p01] After three chapters, he had a vivid idea of a boy seeing a man's beheading and finding direwolves in the snow, which would eventually become the first non-prologue chapter of *A Game of Thrones*.
[src:northwestern-university/a-song-of-ice-and-fire-p01] Putting *Avalon* aside, Martin finished this chapter in a few days and grew certain that it was part of a longer story.
[src:northwestern-university/a-song-of-ice-and-fire-p01] After a few more chapters, Martin perceived his new book as a fantasy story and started making maps and genealogies.
[src:northwestern-university/a-song-of-ice-and-fire-p01] However, the writing of this book was interrupted for a few years when Martin returned to Hollywood to produce his TV series *Doorways* that ABC had ordered but ultimately never aired.
[src:northwestern-university/a-song-of-ice-and-fire-p01] In 1994, Martin gave his agent, Kirby McCauley, the first 200 pages and a two-page story projection as part of a planned trilogy with the novels *A Dance with Dragons* and *The Winds of Winter* intended to follow.
[src:northwestern-university/a-song-of-ice-and-fire-p01] When Martin had still not reached the novel's end at 1,400 manuscript pages, he felt that the series needed to be four and eventually six books long, which he imagined as two linked trilogies of one long story.
[src:northwestern-university/a-song-of-ice-and-fire-p01] Martin also named Robert Frost's 1920 poem "Fire and Ice" and cultural associations such as passion versus betrayal as possible influences for the series' title.
[src:northwestern-university/a-song-of-ice-and-fire-p01] The revised finished manuscript for *A Game of Thrones* was 1,088 pages long (without the appendices), with the publication following in August 1996.
[src:northwestern-university/a-song-of-ice-and-fire-p01] *The Wheel of Time*author Robert Jordan had written a short endorsement for the cover that was influential in ensuring the book's and hence series' early success with fantasy readers.
[src:northwestern-university/a-song-of-ice-and-fire-p01] *Blood of the Dragon*, a pre-release sample novella drawn from Daenerys's chapters, went on to win the 1997 Hugo Award for Best Novella.
[src:northwestern-university/a-song-of-ice-and-fire-p01] The first book was marketed as part of the "*Song of Ice and Fire* trilogy" in 1996, but by the second book's release, the "trilogy" suffix had been dropped and the series was retitled to *A Song of Ice and Fire*.
[src:northwestern-university/a-song-of-ice-and-fire-p01] The 300 pages removed from the *Game of Thrones* manuscript served as the opening of the second book, entitled *A Clash of Kings*.
[src:northwestern-university/a-song-of-ice-and-fire-p01] It was released in February 1999 in the United States, with a manuscript length (without appendices) of 1,184 pages.
[src:northwestern-university/a-song-of-ice-and-fire-p01] *A Clash of Kings* was the first book of the *Song of Ice and Fire* series to make the best-seller lists, reaching 13 on *The New York Times* Best Seller list in 1999.
[src:northwestern-university/a-song-of-ice-and-fire-p01] After the success of *The Lord of the Rings* films, Martin received his first inquiries to the rights of the *Song of Ice and Fire* series from various producers and filmmakers.
[src:northwestern-university/a-song-of-ice-and-fire-p01] Martin was several months late turning in the third book, *A Storm of Swords*.
[src:northwestern-university/a-song-of-ice-and-fire-p01] The last chapter he had written was about the "Red Wedding", a pivotal scene notable for its violence (see Themes: Violence and death).
[src:northwestern-university/a-song-of-ice-and-fire-p01] *A Storm of Swords* was 1,521 pages in manuscript (without appendices), causing problems for many of Martin's publishers around the world.
[src:northwestern-university/a-song-of-ice-and-fire-p01] Bantam Books published *A Storm of Swords* in a single volume in the United States in November 2000, whereas some other-language editions were divided into two, three, or even four volumes.
[src:northwestern-university/a-song-of-ice-and-fire-p01] *A Storm of Swords* debuted at number 12 in the *New York Times* bestseller list.
[src:northwestern-university/a-song-of-ice-and-fire-p01] After *A Game of Thrones*, *A Clash of Kings*, and *A Storm of Swords*, Martin originally intended to write three more books.
[src:northwestern-university/a-song-of-ice-and-fire-p01] The fourth book, tentatively titled *A Dance with Dragons*, was to focus on Daenerys Targaryen's return to Westeros and the associated conflicts.
[src:northwestern-university/a-song-of-ice-and-fire-p01] Martin wanted to set this story five years after *A Storm of Swords* so that the younger characters could grow older and the dragons could grow larger.
[src:northwestern-university/a-song-of-ice-and-fire-p01] Agreeing with his publishers early on that the new book should be shorter than *A Storm of Swords*, Martin set out to write the novel closer in length to *A Clash of Kings*.
[src:northwestern-university/a-song-of-ice-and-fire-p01] A long prologue was to establish what had happened in the meantime, initially just as one chapter of Aeron Damphair on the Iron Islands at the Kingsmoot.
[src:northwestern-university/a-song-of-ice-and-fire-p01] Since the events on the Iron Islands were to have an impact in the book and could not be told with existing POV characters, Martin eventually introduced three new viewpoints.
[src:northwestern-university/a-song-of-ice-and-fire-p01] In 2001, Martin was still optimistic that the fourth installment might be released in the last quarter of 2002.
[src:northwestern-university/a-song-of-ice-and-fire-p01] However, the five-year gap did not work for all characters during writing.
[src:northwestern-university/a-song-of-ice-and-fire-p01] On one hand, Martin was unsatisfied with covering the events during the gap solely through flashbacks and internal retrospection.
[src:northwestern-university/a-song-of-ice-and-fire-p01] On the other hand, it was implausible to have nothing happen for five years.
[src:northwestern-university/a-song-of-ice-and-fire-p01] After working on the book for about a year, Martin realized he needed an additional interim book, which he called *A Feast for Crows*.
[src:northwestern-university/a-song-of-ice-and-fire-p01] The book would pick up the story immediately after the third book, and Martin scrapped the idea of a five-year gap.
[src:northwestern-university/a-song-of-ice-and-fire-p01] The material of the written 250-page prologue was mixed in as new viewpoint characters from Dorne and the Iron Islands.
[src:northwestern-university/a-song-of-ice-and-fire-p01] These expanded storylines and the resulting story interactions complicated the plot for Martin.
[src:northwestern-university/a-song-of-ice-and-fire-p01] The manuscript length of *A Feast for Crows* eventually surpassed *A Storm of Swords*.
[src:northwestern-university/a-song-of-ice-and-fire-p01] Martin was reluctant to make the necessary deep cuts to get the book down to publishable length, as that would have compromised the story he had in mind.
[src:northwestern-university/a-song-of-ice-and-fire-p01] Printing the book in "microtype on onion skin paper and giving each reader a magnifying glass" was also not an option for him.
[src:northwestern-university/a-song-of-ice-and-fire-p01] On the other hand, Martin rejected the publishers' idea of splitting the narrative chronologically into *A Feast for Crows*, Parts One and Two.
[src:northwestern-university/a-song-of-ice-and-fire-p01] Being already late with the book, Martin had not even started writing all characters' stories, and also objected to ending the first book without any resolution for its many viewpoint characters as in previous books.
[src:northwestern-university/a-song-of-ice-and-fire-p01] With the characters spread out across the world, a friend suggested that Martin divide the story geographically into two volumes, of which *A Feast for Crows* would be the first.
[src:northwestern-university/a-song-of-ice-and-fire-p01] This approach would give Martin the room to complete his commenced story arcs as he had originally intended, which he still felt was the best approach years later.
[src:northwestern-university/a-song-of-ice-and-fire-p01] Martin moved the unfinished characters' stories set in the east (Essos) and north (Winterfell and the Wall) into the next book, *A Dance with Dragons*, and left *A Feast for Crows* to cover the events in King's Landing, the Riverlands, Dorne, and the Iron Islands.
[src:northwestern-university/a-song-of-ice-and-fire-p01] Both books begin immediately after the end of *A Storm of Swords*, running in parallel instead of sequentially, and involve different casts of characters with only little overlap.
[src:northwestern-university/a-song-of-ice-and-fire-p01] Martin split Arya's chapters into both books after having already moved the three other most popular characters (Jon Snow, Tyrion, and Daenerys) into *A Dance with Dragons*.
[src:northwestern-university/a-song-of-ice-and-fire-p01] Upon its release in October 2005 in the UK and November 2005 in the US, *A Feast for Crows* went straight to the top of *The New York Times* bestseller list.
[src:northwestern-university/a-song-of-ice-and-fire-p01] Among the positive reviewers was Lev Grossman of *Time*, who dubbed Martin "the American Tolkien".
[src:northwestern-university/a-song-of-ice-and-fire-p01] However, fans and critics alike were disappointed with the story split that left the fates of several popular characters unresolved after *A Storm of Swords*' cliffhanger ending.
[src:northwestern-university/a-song-of-ice-and-fire-p01] With *A Dance with Dragons* said to be half-finished, Martin mentioned in the epilogue of *A Feast for Crows* that the next volume would be released by the next year.
[src:northwestern-university/a-song-of-ice-and-fire-p01] However, planned release dates were repeatedly pushed back.
[src:northwestern-university/a-song-of-ice-and-fire-p01] Meanwhile, HBO acquired the rights to turn *A Song of Ice and Fire* into a fantasy drama series in 2007 and aired the first of ten episodes covering *A Game of Thrones* in April 2011.
[src:northwestern-university/a-song-of-ice-and-fire-p01] With around 1600 pages in manuscript length, *A Dance with Dragons* was eventually published in July 2011 after six years of writing, longer in page count and writing time than any of the preceding four novels.
[src:northwestern-university/a-song-of-ice-and-fire-p01] The story of *A Dance with Dragons* catches up with and goes beyond *A Feast for Crows* around two-thirds into the book, but nevertheless covers less story than Martin had intended, omitting at least one planned large battle sequence and leaving several character threads ending in cliffhangers.
[src:northwestern-university/a-song-of-ice-and-fire-p01] Martin attributed the delay mainly to his untangling "the Meereenese knot", which the interviewer understood as "making the chronology and characters mesh up as various threads converged on [Daenerys]".
[src:northwestern-university/a-song-of-ice-and-fire-p01] Martin also acknowledged spending too much time on rewriting and perfecting the story, but soundly rejected the theories of some of his critics that he had lost interest in the series or would bide his time to make more money.
[src:northwestern-university/a-song-of-ice-and-fire-p01] Martin believed in 2012 the last two volumes of the series would be large books of 1500 manuscript pages each.
[src:northwestern-university/a-song-of-ice-and-fire-p01] The sixth book will be called *The Winds of Winter*, taking the title of the last book of the originally planned trilogy.
[src:northwestern-university/a-song-of-ice-and-fire-p01] Displeased with the provisional title *A Time for Wolves* for the final volume, Martin ultimately chose *A Dream of Spring* as the title for the seventh book in 2006.
[src:northwestern-university/a-song-of-ice-and-fire-p01] Martin said in March 2012 that the final two novels will take readers farther north than any of the previous books, and that the Others will appear.
[src:northwestern-university/a-song-of-ice-and-fire-p01] Martin indicated he would not permit another writer to finish the book series.
[src:northwestern-university/a-song-of-ice-and-fire-p01] In 2011, Martin gave three years as a realistic estimate for finishing the sixth book at a good pace, but said ultimately the book "will be done when it's done", acknowledging that his publication estimates had been too optimistic in the past.
[src:northwestern-university/a-song-of-ice-and-fire-p01] In 2015 there were indications that the book would be published before the sixth season of the HBO show but in early January 2016 Martin confirmed that he had not met an end-of-year deadline that he had established with his publisher for release of the book before the sixth season.
[src:northwestern-university/a-song-of-ice-and-fire-p01] He also revealed there had been a previous deadline of October 2015 that he had considered achievable in May 2015, and that in September 2015 he had still considered the end-of-year deadline achievable.
[src:northwestern-university/a-song-of-ice-and-fire-p01] He further confirmed that some of the plot of the book might be revealed in the then-upcoming sixth season of *Game of Thrones*.
[src:northwestern-university/a-song-of-ice-and-fire-p01] In February 2016, Martin stated that he dropped all his editing projects except for *Wild Cards*, and that he would not be writing any teleplays, screenplays, short stories, introductions or forewords before delivering *The Winds of Winter*.
[src:northwestern-university/a-song-of-ice-and-fire-p01] In March 2020, Martin stated that he was writing *The Winds of Winter* every day, and in June he hoped to be done with it in 2021.
[src:northwestern-university/a-song-of-ice-and-fire-p01] In October 2022, Martin said that he had written approximately three quarters of the book. estimating that he had written approximately 1,100 to 1,200 pages, and had roughly 400 to 500 pages left.
[src:northwestern-university/a-song-of-ice-and-fire-p01] He gave a similar estimate in November 2023, saying that he was "struggling" with the manuscript.
[src:northwestern-university/a-song-of-ice-and-fire-p01] Martin is not firm about ending the series with the seventh novel.
[src:northwestern-university/a-song-of-ice-and-fire-p01] With his stated goal of telling the story from beginning to end, he will not truncate the story to fit into an arbitrary number of volumes.
[src:northwestern-university/a-song-of-ice-and-fire-p01] He knows the ending in broad strokes as well as the future of the main characters, and plans to finish the series with bittersweet elements where not everyone will live happily ever after.
[src:northwestern-university/a-song-of-ice-and-fire-p01] Martin hopes to write an ending similar to *The Lord of the Rings* that he felt gave the story a satisfying depth and resonance.
[src:northwestern-university/a-song-of-ice-and-fire-p01] On the other hand, Martin noted the challenge to avoid a situation like the finale of the TV series *Lost*, which left some fans disappointed by deviating too far from their own theories and desires.
[src:northwestern-university/a-song-of-ice-and-fire-p01] In 2015, Martin said that he was not writing *A Dream of Spring* together with *The Winds of Winter*, and in early 2016, he said he did not believe *A Dream of Spring* would be published before the last season of the HBO show.
[src:northwestern-university/a-song-of-ice-and-fire-p01] In May 2019, Martin reiterated he had not started writing *A Dream of Spring* and would not do so before finishing *The Winds of Winter*.
[src:northwestern-university/a-song-of-ice-and-fire-p01] Regarding *A Song of Ice and Fire* as his masterpiece, Martin stated he would never write anything on this scale again and would only return to this fictional universe in the context of stand-alone novels.
[src:northwestern-university/a-song-of-ice-and-fire-p01] He prefers to write stories about characters from other *A Song of Ice and Fire* periods of history such as his *Tales of Dunk and Egg* project, instead of continuing the series directly.
[src:northwestern-university/a-song-of-ice-and-fire-p01] Martin said he would love to return to writing short stories, novellas, novelettes, and stand-alone novels from diverse genres such as science fiction, horror, fantasy, or even a murder mystery.
[src:northwestern-university/a-song-of-ice-and-fire-p01] Martin believes the most profound influences to be the ones experienced in childhood.
[src:northwestern-university/a-song-of-ice-and-fire-p01] Heinlein, Eric Frank Russell, Andre Norton, Isaac Asimov, Fritz Leiber, and Mervyn Peake in his youth, Martin never categorized these authors' literature into science fiction, fantasy, or horror and will write from any genre as a result.
[src:northwestern-university/a-song-of-ice-and-fire-p01] Martin classified *A Song of Ice and Fire* as "epic fantasy", and specifically named Tad Williams' high fantasy epic *Memory, Sorrow, and Thorn* as very influential for the writing of the series.
[src:northwestern-university/a-song-of-ice-and-fire-p01] One of his favorite authors is Jack Vance, although Martin considered the series not particularly Vancean.
[src:northwestern-university/a-song-of-ice-and-fire-p01] Martin experienced some harsh winters when living in Dubuque a few years in the 1970s, and suspects these winters had an influence on his writing: "I think a lot of the stuff in *A Game of Thrones*, the snow and ice and freezing, comes from my memories of Dubuque".
[src:northwestern-university/a-song-of-ice-and-fire-p01] The medieval setting has been the traditional background for epic fantasy.
[src:northwestern-university/a-song-of-ice-and-fire-p01] However, where historical fiction leaves versed readers knowing the historical outcome, original characters may increase suspense and empathy for the readers.
[src:northwestern-university/a-song-of-ice-and-fire-p01] Yet Martin felt historical fiction, particularly when set during the Middle Ages, had an excitement, grittiness, and a realness to it that was absent in fantasy with a similar backdrop.
[src:northwestern-university/a-song-of-ice-and-fire-p01] Thus, he wanted to combine the realism of historical fiction with the magic appeal of the best fantasies, subduing magic in favor of battles and political intrigue.
[src:northwestern-university/a-song-of-ice-and-fire-p01] He also decided to avoid the conventional good versus evil setting typical for the genre, using the fight between Achilles and Hector in Homer's *Iliad*, where no one stands out as either a hero or a villain, as an example of what he wants to achieve with his books.
[src:northwestern-university/a-song-of-ice-and-fire-p01] Martin is widely credited with broadening the fantasy fiction genre for adult content.
[src:northwestern-university/a-song-of-ice-and-fire-p01] Writing for *The Atlantic*, Amber Taylor assessed the novels as hard fantasy with vulnerable characters to which readers become emotionally attached.
[src:northwestern-university/a-song-of-ice-and-fire-p01] CNN found in 2000 that Martin's mature descriptions were "far more frank than those found in the works of other fantasy authors", although Martin assessed the fantasy genre to have become rougher-edged a decade later and that some writers' work was going beyond the mature themes of his novels.
[src:northwestern-university/a-song-of-ice-and-fire-p01] Adam Roberts called Martin's series the most successful and popular example of the emerging subgenre of grimdark fantasy.
[src:northwestern-university/a-song-of-ice-and-fire-p01] Setting out to write something on an epic scale, Martin projected to write three books of 800 manuscript pages in the very early stages of the series.
[src:northwestern-university/a-song-of-ice-and-fire-p01] His original 1990s contract specified one-year deadlines for his previous literary works, but Martin only realized later that his new books were longer and hence required more writing time.
[src:northwestern-university/a-song-of-ice-and-fire-p01] In 2000, Martin planned to take 18 months to two years for each volume and projected the last of the planned six books to be released five or six years later.
[src:northwestern-university/a-song-of-ice-and-fire-p01] However, with *A Song of Ice and Fire* series evolving into the biggest and most ambitious story he has ever attempted writing, he still has two more books to finish as of 2025.
[src:northwestern-university/a-song-of-ice-and-fire-p01] Martin said he needed to be in his own office in Santa Fe, New Mexico to immerse himself in the fictional world and write.
[src:northwestern-university/a-song-of-ice-and-fire-p01] As of 2011, Martin was still typing his fiction on an IBM PC compatible computer running MS-DOS with WordStar 4.0.
[src:northwestern-university/a-song-of-ice-and-fire-p01] He begins each day at 10 am with rewriting and polishing the previous day's work, and may write all day or struggle to write anything.
[src:northwestern-university/a-song-of-ice-and-fire-p01] Excised material and previous old versions are saved to be possibly re-inserted at a later time.
[src:northwestern-university/a-song-of-ice-and-fire-p01] Martin does not consider *A Song of Ice and Fire* a "series" but a single story published in several volumes.
[src:northwestern-university/a-song-of-ice-and-fire-p01] Martin set the *A Song of Ice and Fire* story in a secondary world inspired by Tolkien's writing.
[src:northwestern-university/a-song-of-ice-and-fire-p01] Unlike Tolkien, who created entire languages, mythologies, and histories for Middle-earth long before writing *The Lord of the Rings*, Martin usually starts with a rough sketch of an imaginary world that he improvises into a workable fictional setting along the way.
[src:northwestern-university/a-song-of-ice-and-fire-p01] He described his writing as coming from a subconscious level in "almost a daydreaming process", and his stories, which have a mythic rather than a scientific core, draw from emotion instead of rationality.
[src:northwestern-university/a-song-of-ice-and-fire-p01] Martin employs maps and a cast list topping 60 pages in the fourth volume, but keeps most information in his mind.
[src:northwestern-university/a-song-of-ice-and-fire-p01] His imagined backstory remains subject to change until published, and only the novels count as canon.
[src:northwestern-university/a-song-of-ice-and-fire-p01] Martin does not intend to publish his private notes after the series is finished.
[src:northwestern-university/a-song-of-ice-and-fire-p01] Martin drew much inspiration from actual history for the series, having several bookcases filled with medieval history for research and visiting historic European landmarks.
[src:northwestern-university/a-song-of-ice-and-fire-p01] For an American who speaks only English, the history of England proved the easiest source of medieval history for him, giving the series a British rather than a German or Spanish historic flavor.
[src:northwestern-university/a-song-of-ice-and-fire-p01] For example, Ned and Robb Stark resemble Richard, 3rd Duke of York, and his son Edward IV, and Queen Cersei resembles both Margaret of Anjou and Elizabeth Woodville.
[src:northwestern-university/a-song-of-ice-and-fire-p01] Martin immersed himself in many diverse medieval topics such as clothing, food, feasting, and tournaments to have the facts at hand if needed during writing.
[src:northwestern-university/a-song-of-ice-and-fire-p01] The series was in particular influenced by the Hundred Years' War, the Crusades, the Albigensian Crusade, and the Wars of the Roses, although Martin refrained from making any direct adaptations.
[src:northwestern-university/a-song-of-ice-and-fire-p01] Martin was also inspired by the French historical novels *The Accursed Kings* by Maurice Druon, which are about the French monarchy in the 13th and 14th centuries.
[src:northwestern-university/a-song-of-ice-and-fire-p01] Martin has also said that important events of the narrative, such as the "Red Wedding", a crucial plot point in *A Storm of Swords*, are based on events in Scottish history such as the Black Dinner of 1440 and the Massacre of Glencoe in 1692.
[src:northwestern-university/a-song-of-ice-and-fire-p01] Martin has also drawn from Roman history for inspiration, comparing Stannis Baratheon to the Roman Emperor Tiberius.
[src:northwestern-university/a-song-of-ice-and-fire-p01] The story is written to follow principal landmarks with an ultimate destination, but leaves Martin room for improvisation.
[src:northwestern-university/a-song-of-ice-and-fire-p01] On occasion, improvised details significantly affected the planned story.
[src:northwestern-university/a-song-of-ice-and-fire-p01] By the fourth book, Martin kept more private notes than ever before to keep track of the many subplots, which became so detailed and sprawling by the fifth book as to be unwieldy.
[src:northwestern-university/a-song-of-ice-and-fire-p01] Martin's editors, copy editors, and readers monitor for accidental mistakes, although some errors have slipped into publication.
[src:northwestern-university/a-song-of-ice-and-fire-p01] For instance, Martin has inconsistently referred to certain characters' eye colors, and has described a horse as being of one sex and then another.
[src:northwestern-university/a-song-of-ice-and-fire-p01] The books are divided into chapters, each one narrated in the third person limited through the eyes of a point of view character, an approach Martin learned himself as a young journalism student.
[src:northwestern-university/a-song-of-ice-and-fire-p01] Beginning with nine POV characters in *A Game of Thrones*, the number of POV characters grows to a total of 31 in *A Dance with Dragons* (see table).
[src:northwestern-university/a-song-of-ice-and-fire-p01] The short-lived one-time POV characters are mostly restricted to the prologues and epilogues.
[src:northwestern-university/a-song-of-ice-and-fire-p01] However, as *Time*'s Lev Grossman noted, readers "experience the struggle for Westeros from all sides at once", such that "every fight is both triumph and tragedy [...] and everybody is both hero and villain at the same time".
[src:northwestern-university/a-song-of-ice-and-fire-p01] Modeled on *The Lord of the Rings*, the story of *A Song of Ice and Fire* begins with a tight focus on a small group (with everyone in Winterfell, except Daenerys) and then splits into separate stories.
[src:northwestern-university/a-song-of-ice-and-fire-p01] The storylines are to converge again, but finding the turning point in this complex series has been difficult for Martin and has slowed down his writing.
[src:northwestern-university/a-song-of-ice-and-fire-p01] Depending on the interview, Martin is said to have reached the turning point in *A Dance with Dragons*, or to not quite have reached it yet in the books.
[src:northwestern-university/a-song-of-ice-and-fire-p01] The series' structure of multiple POVs and interwoven storylines was inspired by *Wild Cards*, a multi-authored shared universe book series edited by Martin since 1985.
[src:northwestern-university/a-song-of-ice-and-fire-p01] As the sole author, Martin begins each new book with an outline of the chapter order and may write a few successive chapters from a single character's viewpoint instead of working chronologically.
[src:northwestern-university/a-song-of-ice-and-fire-p01] The chapters are later rearranged to optimize character intercutting, chronology, and suspense.
[src:northwestern-university/a-song-of-ice-and-fire-p01] Influenced by his television and film scripting background, Martin tries to keep readers engrossed by ending each *Song of Ice and Fire* chapter with a tense or revelational moment, a twist or a cliffhanger, similar to a TV act break.
[src:northwestern-university/a-song-of-ice-and-fire-p01] Scriptwriting has also taught him the technique of "cutting out the fat and leaving the muscle", which is the final stage of completing a book, a technique that brought the page count in *A Dance with Dragons* down almost eighty pages.
[src:northwestern-university/a-song-of-ice-and-fire-p01] Dividing the continuous *Song of Ice and Fire* story into books is much harder for Martin.
[src:northwestern-university/a-song-of-ice-and-fire-p01] Each book shall represent a phase of the journey that ends in closure for most characters.
[src:northwestern-university/a-song-of-ice-and-fire-p01] A smaller portion of characters is left with clear-cut cliffhangers to make sure readers come back for the next installment, although *A Dance with Dragons* had more cliffhangers than Martin originally intended.
[src:northwestern-university/a-song-of-ice-and-fire-p01] Both one-time and regular POV characters are designed to have full character arcs ending in tragedy or triumph, and are written to hold the readers' interest and not be skipped in reading.
[src:northwestern-university/a-song-of-ice-and-fire-p01] Main characters are killed off so that the reader will not rely on the hero to come through unscathed and will instead feel the character's fear with each page turn.
[src:northwestern-university/a-song-of-ice-and-fire-p01] The unresolved larger narrative arc encourages speculation about future story events.
[src:northwestern-university/a-song-of-ice-and-fire-p01] According to Martin, much of the key to *A Song of Ice and Fire*'s future lies over a dozen years in the fictional past, of which each volume reveals more.
[src:northwestern-university/a-song-of-ice-and-fire-p01] Events planned from the beginning are foreshadowed, although Martin is careful not to make the story predictable.
[src:northwestern-university/a-song-of-ice-and-fire-p01] The viewpoint characters, who serve as unreliable narrators, may clarify or provide different perspectives on past events.
[src:northwestern-university/a-song-of-ice-and-fire-p01] Therefore, what the readers believe to be true may not necessarily be true.
[src:northwestern-university/a-song-of-ice-and-fire-p01] Regarding the characters as the heart of the story, Martin planned the epic *A Song of Ice and Fire* to have a large cast of characters and many different settings from the beginning.
[src:northwestern-university/a-song-of-ice-and-fire-p01] *A Feast for Crows* has a 63-page list of characters, with many of the thousands of characters mentioned only in passing or disappearing from view for long stretches.
[src:northwestern-university/a-song-of-ice-and-fire-p01] When Martin adds a new family to the ever-growing number of genealogies in the appendices, he devises a secret about the personality or fate of the family members.
[src:northwestern-university/a-song-of-ice-and-fire-p01] However, their backstory remains subject to change until written down in the story.
[src:northwestern-university/a-song-of-ice-and-fire-p01] Martin drew most character inspiration from history (without directly translating historical figures) and his own experiences, but also from the manners of his friends, acquaintances, and people of public interest.
[src:northwestern-university/a-song-of-ice-and-fire-p01] Martin aims to "make my characters real and to make them human, characters who have good and bad, noble and selfish well-mixed in their natures".
[src:northwestern-university/a-song-of-ice-and-fire-p01] Jeff VanderMeer of the *Los Angeles Times* remarked that "Martin's devotion to fully inhabiting his characters, for better or worse, creates the unstoppable momentum in his novels and contains an implied criticism of Tolkien's moral simplicity" (see Themes: Moral ambiguity).
[src:northwestern-university/a-song-of-ice-and-fire-p01] Martin deliberately ignored the writing rule of never giving two characters names starting with the same letter.
[src:northwestern-university/a-song-of-ice-and-fire-p01] Instead, character names reflect the naming systems in various European family histories, where particular names were associated with specific royal houses and where even the secondary families assigned the same names repeatedly.
[src:northwestern-university/a-song-of-ice-and-fire-p01] The story of *A Song of Ice and Fire* therefore has children called "Robert" in honor of King Robert of House Baratheon, a "Brandon" in many generations of the Starks in commemoration of Brandon the Builder (of the Wall), and the syllable "Ty" commonly occurring in given names of House Lannister.
[src:northwestern-university/a-song-of-ice-and-fire-p01] Confident that readers would pay attention, Martin distinguished people sharing a given name by adding numbers or locations to their given names (e.g.
[src:northwestern-university/a-song-of-ice-and-fire-p01] All characters are designed to speak with their own internal voices to capture their views of the world.
[src:northwestern-university/a-song-of-ice-and-fire-p01] *The Atlantic* pondered whether Martin ultimately intended the readers to sympathize with characters on both sides of the Lannister–Stark feud long before plot developments force them to make their emotional choices.
[src:northwestern-university/a-song-of-ice-and-fire-p01] Seeing the world through the characters' eyes requires a certain amount of empathy with them, including the villains, all of whom he has said he loves as if they were his own children.
[src:northwestern-university/a-song-of-ice-and-fire-p01] Martin found that some characters had minds of their own and took his writing in different directions.
[src:northwestern-university/a-song-of-ice-and-fire-p01] He returns to the intended story if it does not work out, but these detours sometimes prove more rewarding for him.
[src:northwestern-university/a-song-of-ice-and-fire-p01] Arya Stark, Tyrion Lannister, Jon Snow, and Daenerys Targaryen generate the most feedback from readers.
[src:northwestern-university/a-song-of-ice-and-fire-p01] They are also four of the "big six" main characters of the series, according to Martin (the other two being Sansa Stark and Bran Stark).
[src:northwestern-university/a-song-of-ice-and-fire-p01] Martin has stated that Tyrion is his personal favorite, as the grayest of the gray characters, with his cunning and wit making him the most fun to write.
[src:northwestern-university/a-song-of-ice-and-fire-p01] Martin has also said that Bran Stark is the hardest character to write.
[src:northwestern-university/a-song-of-ice-and-fire-p01] As the character most deeply involved in magic, Bran's story needs to be handled carefully within the supernatural aspects of the books.
[src:northwestern-university/a-song-of-ice-and-fire-p01] Bran is also the youngest viewpoint character, and has to deal with the series' adult themes like grief, loneliness, and anger.
[src:northwestern-university/a-song-of-ice-and-fire-p01] Martin set out to have the young characters grow up faster between chapters, but, as it was implausible for a character to take two months to respond, a finished book represents very little time passed.
[src:northwestern-university/a-song-of-ice-and-fire-p01] Martin hoped the planned five-year break would ease the situation and age the children to almost adults in terms of the Seven Kingdoms, but he later dropped the five-year gap (see section Bridging the timeline gap).
[src:northwestern-university/a-song-of-ice-and-fire-p01] Wheareas modern fantasy often embraces magical elements, *A Song of Ice and Fire* series is generally praised for what is perceived as a sort of medieval realism.
[src:northwestern-university/a-song-of-ice-and-fire-p01] Believing that magic should be used moderately in the epic fantasy genre, Martin set out to make the story feel more like historical fiction than contemporary fantasy, with less emphasis on magic and more on battles, political intrigue, and the characters.
[src:northwestern-university/a-song-of-ice-and-fire-p01] Though the amount of magic has gradually increased throughout the story, the series is still to end with less overt magic than most contemporary fantasies.
[src:northwestern-university/a-song-of-ice-and-fire-p01] In Martin's eyes, literary effective magic needs to represent strange and dangerous forces beyond human comprehension, not advanced alien technologies or formulaic spells.
[src:northwestern-university/a-song-of-ice-and-fire-p01] As such, the characters understand only the natural aspects of their world, but not the magical elements like the Others.
[src:northwestern-university/a-song-of-ice-and-fire-p01] Since Martin drew on historical sources to build the world of *A Song of Ice and Fire*, Damien G.
[src:northwestern-university/a-song-of-ice-and-fire-p01] Walter of *The Guardian* saw a strong resemblance between Westeros and England in the period of the Wars of the Roses.
[src:northwestern-university/a-song-of-ice-and-fire-p01] Martin not only wanted to reflect the frictions of the medieval class structures in the novels, but also explore the consequences of the leaders' decisions, as general goodness does not automatically make competent leaders and vice versa.
[src:northwestern-university/a-song-of-ice-and-fire-p01] A common theme in the fantasy genre is the battle between good and evil, which Martin rejects for not mirroring the real world.
[src:northwestern-university/a-song-of-ice-and-fire-p01] Attracted to gray characters, Martin instead endorses William Faulkner's view that only the human heart in conflict with itself was worth writing about.
[src:northwestern-university/a-song-of-ice-and-fire-p01] Martin explores the questions of redemption and character change in the *A Song of Ice and Fire* series.
[src:northwestern-university/a-song-of-ice-and-fire-p01] The multiple viewpoint structure allows characters to be explored from many sides, such that the supposed villains can provide their viewpoint.
[src:northwestern-university/a-song-of-ice-and-fire-p01] Although fantasy comes from an imaginative realm, Martin sees an honest necessity to reflect the real world where people, even beloved people, sometimes die ugly deaths.
[src:northwestern-university/a-song-of-ice-and-fire-p01] Main characters are killed off so that the reader will not expect the supposed hero to survive, and instead will feel the same tension and fear that the characters might.
[src:northwestern-university/a-song-of-ice-and-fire-p01] The novels also reflect the substantial death rates in war.
[src:northwestern-university/a-song-of-ice-and-fire-p01] The deaths of supernumerary extras, or of orcs or their equivalents, have no major effect on readers, whereas a friend's death has much more emotional impact.
[src:northwestern-university/a-song-of-ice-and-fire-p01] Martin prefers a hero's sacrifice to say something profound about human nature.
[src:northwestern-university/a-song-of-ice-and-fire-p01] According to Martin, the fantasy genre rarely focuses on sex and sexuality, instead often treating sexuality in a juvenile way or neglecting it completely.
[src:northwestern-university/a-song-of-ice-and-fire-p01] Martin, however, considers sexuality an important driving force in human life that should not be excluded from the narrative.
[src:northwestern-university/a-song-of-ice-and-fire-p01] The non-existent concept of adolescence in the Middle Ages served as a model for Daenerys' sexual activity at the age of 13 in the books.
[src:northwestern-university/a-song-of-ice-and-fire-p01] The novels also allude to the incestuous practices in the Ptolemaic dynasty of Ancient Egypt to keep their bloodlines pure.
[src:northwestern-university/a-song-of-ice-and-fire-p01] Martin provides a variety of female characters to explore the place of women in a patriarchal society.
[src:northwestern-university/a-song-of-ice-and-fire-p01] Writing all characters as human beings with the same basic needs, dreams, and influences, his female characters are to cover the same wide spectrum of human traits as the males.
[src:northwestern-university/a-song-of-ice-and-fire-p02] According to *The Globe and Mail*'s John Barber, Martin manages simultaneously to master and transcend the genre so that "Critics applaud the depth of his characterizations and lack of cliché in books that are nonetheless replete with dwarves and dragons".
[src:northwestern-university/a-song-of-ice-and-fire-p02] However, they found that *A Feast for Crows* as the fourth installment "sorely misses its other half.
[src:northwestern-university/a-song-of-ice-and-fire-p02] Every town has an elaborately recalled series of triumphs and troubles." Salon.com's Andrew Leonard "couldn't stop reading Martin because my desire to know what was going to happen combined with my absolute inability to guess what would happen and left me helpless before his sorcery.
[src:northwestern-university/a-song-of-ice-and-fire-p02] At the end, I felt shaken and exhausted." *The Christian Science Monitor* advised reading the novels with an *A Song of Ice and Fire* encyclopedia at hand to "catch all the layered, subtle hints and details that [Martin] leaves throughout his books.
[src:northwestern-university/a-song-of-ice-and-fire-p02] Among the most critical voices were Sam Jordison and Michael Hann, both of *The Guardian*.
[src:northwestern-university/a-song-of-ice-and-fire-p02] Jordison detailed his misgivings about *A Game of Thrones* in a 2009 review and summarized "It's daft.
[src:northwestern-university/a-song-of-ice-and-fire-p02] Archaic absurdity aside, Martin's writing is excellent.
[src:northwestern-university/a-song-of-ice-and-fire-p02] His dialogue is snappy and frequently funny.
[src:northwestern-university/a-song-of-ice-and-fire-p02] The reported overall sales figures of the *A Song of Ice and Fire* series vary.
[src:northwestern-university/a-song-of-ice-and-fire-p02] *The New Yorker* said in April 2011 (before the publication of *A Dance with Dragons*) that more than 15 million *A Song of Ice and Fire* books had been sold worldwide, a figure repeated by *The Globe and Mail* in July 2011.
[src:northwestern-university/a-song-of-ice-and-fire-p02] Reuters reported in September 2013 that the books including print, digital and audio versions have sold more than 24 million copies in North America.
[src:northwestern-university/a-song-of-ice-and-fire-p02] *The Wall Street Journal* reported more than six million sold copies in North America by May 2011.
[src:northwestern-university/a-song-of-ice-and-fire-p02] *USA Today* reported 8.5 million copies in print and digital overall in July 2011, and over 12 million sold copies in print in December 2011.
[src:northwestern-university/a-song-of-ice-and-fire-p02] The series has been translated into more than 20 languages; *USA Today* reported the fifth book to be translated into over 40 languages.
[src:northwestern-university/a-song-of-ice-and-fire-p02] *Forbes* estimated that Martin was the 12th highest-earning author worldwide in 2011 at $15 million.
[src:northwestern-university/a-song-of-ice-and-fire-p02] Martin's publishers initially expected *A Game of Thrones* to be a best-seller, but the first installment did not even reach any lower positions in the bestseller list.
[src:northwestern-university/a-song-of-ice-and-fire-p02] This left Martin unsurprised, as it is "a fool's game to think anything is going to be successful or to count on it".
[src:northwestern-university/a-song-of-ice-and-fire-p02] However, the book slowly won the passionate advocacy of independent booksellers and the book's popularity grew by word of mouth.
[src:northwestern-university/a-song-of-ice-and-fire-p02] The series' popularity skyrocketed in subsequent volumes, with the second and third volumes making *The New York Times* Best Seller lists in 1999 and 2000, respectively.
[src:northwestern-university/a-song-of-ice-and-fire-p02] The series gained Martin's old writings new attention, and Martin's American publisher Bantam Spectra was to reprint his out-of-print solo novels.
[src:northwestern-university/a-song-of-ice-and-fire-p02] The fourth installment, *A Feast for Crows*, was an immediate best-seller at its 2005 release, hitting number one on "The New York Times" hardcover fiction bestseller list November 27, 2005, which for a fantasy novel suggested that Martin's books were attracting mainstream readers.
[src:northwestern-university/a-song-of-ice-and-fire-p02] The paperback edition of *A Game of Thrones* reached its 34th printing in 2010, surpassing the one million mark.
[src:northwestern-university/a-song-of-ice-and-fire-p02] Before it even premiered, the TV series had boosted sales of the book series, with *A Song of Ice and Fire* approaching triple-digit growth in year-on-year sales.
[src:northwestern-university/a-song-of-ice-and-fire-p02] Bantam was looking forward to seeing the tie-ins boost sales further, and Martin's British publisher Harper Voyager expected readers to rediscover their other epic fantasy literature.
[src:northwestern-university/a-song-of-ice-and-fire-p02] With a reported 4.5 million copies of the first four volumes in print in early 2011, the four volumes re-appeared on the paperback fiction bestseller lists in the second quarter of 2011.
[src:northwestern-university/a-song-of-ice-and-fire-p02] At its point of publication in July 2011, *A Dance with Dragons* was in its sixth print with more than 650,000 hardbacks in print.
[src:northwestern-university/a-song-of-ice-and-fire-p02] It also had the highest single and first-day sales of any new fiction title published in 2011 at that point, with 170,000 hardcovers, 110,000 e-books, and 18,000 audio books reportedly sold on the first day.
[src:northwestern-university/a-song-of-ice-and-fire-p02] *A Dance with Dragons* reached the top of *The New York Times* bestseller list on July 31, 2011.
[src:northwestern-university/a-song-of-ice-and-fire-p02] Unlike most other big titles, the fifth volume sold more physical than digital copies early on, but nevertheless, Martin became the tenth author to sell 1 million Amazon Kindle e-books.
[src:northwestern-university/a-song-of-ice-and-fire-p02] All five volumes and the four-volume boxed set were among the top 100 best-selling books in the United States in 2011 and 2012.
[src:northwestern-university/a-song-of-ice-and-fire-p02] The TV series has contributed significantly boosting sales of both the books and collectibles like box-sets, merchandise, and other items.
[src:northwestern-university/a-song-of-ice-and-fire-p02] The TV series also contributed to increasing the geographic coverage of the books, introducing new customers in emerging countries like India and Brazil to the book series.
[src:northwestern-university/a-song-of-ice-and-fire-p02] All this has significantly increased the overall book sales.
[src:northwestern-university/a-song-of-ice-and-fire-p02] As of April 2019, the book series has sold 90 million copies worldwide.
[src:northwestern-university/a-song-of-ice-and-fire-p02] During the 1980s and early 1990s, Martin's novels had slowly earned him a reputation in science fiction circles, although he said to only have received a few fans' letters a year in the pre-internet days.
[src:northwestern-university/a-song-of-ice-and-fire-p02] The publication of *A Game of Thrones* caused Martin's following to grow, with fan sites springing up and a Trekkie-like society of followers evolving that meet regularly.
[src:northwestern-university/a-song-of-ice-and-fire-p02] Westeros.org, one of the main *A Song of Ice and Fire* fansites with about seventeen thousand registered members as of 2011, was co-founded in 1999 by a Swedish-based fan of Cuban descent, Elio M.
[src:northwestern-university/a-song-of-ice-and-fire-p02] García Jr., as well as Linda Antonsson, who introduced him to the series; their involvement with Martin's work has now become semi-professional.
[src:northwestern-university/a-song-of-ice-and-fire-p02] The Brotherhood Without Banners, an unofficial fan club operating globally, was formed in 2001.
[src:northwestern-university/a-song-of-ice-and-fire-p02] Their founders and other longtime members are among Martin's good friends.
[src:northwestern-university/a-song-of-ice-and-fire-p02] Martin runs an official website and administers a lively blog with the assistance of Ty Franck.
[src:northwestern-university/a-song-of-ice-and-fire-p02] He also interacts with fandom by answering emails and letters, although he stated in 2005 that their sheer numbers might leave them unanswered for years.
[src:northwestern-university/a-song-of-ice-and-fire-p02] Since there are different types of conventions nowadays, he tends to go to three or four science-fiction conventions a year simply to go back to his roots and meet friends.
[src:northwestern-university/a-song-of-ice-and-fire-p02] He does not read message boards anymore, so that his writing will not be influenced by fans foreseeing twists and interpreting characters differently from what he intended.
[src:northwestern-university/a-song-of-ice-and-fire-p02] While Martin calls the majority of his fans "great", and enjoys interacting with them, he lost some of them because of the six years it took to release *A Dance with Dragons*.
[src:northwestern-university/a-song-of-ice-and-fire-p02] *The New York Times* noted that it was not uncommon for Martin to be mobbed at book signings.
[src:northwestern-university/a-song-of-ice-and-fire-p02] *The New Yorker* called this "an astonishing amount of effort to devote to denouncing the author of books one professes to love.
[src:northwestern-university/a-song-of-ice-and-fire-p02] The *Tales of Dunk and Egg* series, three novellas set 90 years before the events of the novel series, feature the adventures of Ser Duncan the Tall and his squire "Egg", who later became King Aegon V Targaryen.
[src:northwestern-university/a-song-of-ice-and-fire-p02] The stories have no direct connection to the plot of *A Song of Ice and Fire*, although characters from it are mentioned in the series.
[src:northwestern-university/a-song-of-ice-and-fire-p02] The first installment, *The Hedge Knight*, was published in the 1998 anthology *Legends*.
[src:northwestern-university/a-song-of-ice-and-fire-p02] *The Sworn Sword* followed in 2003, published in *Legends II*.
[src:northwestern-university/a-song-of-ice-and-fire-p02] Both were later adapted into graphic novels.
[src:northwestern-university/a-song-of-ice-and-fire-p02] The third novella, *The Mystery Knight*, was first published in the 2010 anthology *Warriors* and in 2017 it was adapted as a graphic novel, as well.
[src:northwestern-university/a-song-of-ice-and-fire-p02] In 2015, the first three novellas were published as one illustrated collection, *A Knight of the Seven Kingdoms*.
[src:northwestern-university/a-song-of-ice-and-fire-p02] The novella *The Princess and the Queen, or, the Blacks and the Greens* appeared in Tor Books's 2013 anthology *Dangerous Women* and explains some of the Targaryen backstory two centuries before the events of the novels.
[src:northwestern-university/a-song-of-ice-and-fire-p02] *The Rogue Prince, or, a King's Brother*, published in the 2014 anthology *Rogues*, is itself a prequel to the events of *The Princess and the Queen*.
[src:northwestern-university/a-song-of-ice-and-fire-p02] The novella *The Sons of the Dragon*, published in the 2017 anthology *The Book of Swords*, is the story of Aegon the Conqueror's two sons Aenys I and Maegor I "The Cruel".
[src:northwestern-university/a-song-of-ice-and-fire-p02] All three of these stories were incorporated as parts of *Fire & Blood*, a book chronicling Martin's complete history of the House Targaryen line, released in two volumes.
[src:northwestern-university/a-song-of-ice-and-fire-p02] The first volume was released on November 20, 2018.
[src:northwestern-university/a-song-of-ice-and-fire-p02] With the popularity of the series growing, HBO optioned *A Song of Ice and Fire* for a television adaptation in 2007.
[src:northwestern-university/a-song-of-ice-and-fire-p02] A pilot episode was produced in late 2009, and a series commitment for nine further episodes was made in March 2010.
[src:northwestern-university/a-song-of-ice-and-fire-p02] The series, titled *Game of Thrones*, premiered in April 2011 to great acclaim and ratings (see *Game of Thrones* § Reception).
[src:northwestern-university/a-song-of-ice-and-fire-p02] The network picked up the show for a second season covering *A Clash of Kings* two days later.
[src:northwestern-university/a-song-of-ice-and-fire-p02] Shortly after the conclusion of the first season, the show received 13 Emmy Award nominations, including Outstanding Drama Series, winning Outstanding Main Title Design and Outstanding Supporting Actor in a Drama Series for Peter Dinklage's portrayal of Tyrion Lannister.
[src:northwestern-university/a-song-of-ice-and-fire-p02] HBO renewed *Game of Thrones* for a third season in April 2012, ten days after the season 2 premiere.
[src:northwestern-university/a-song-of-ice-and-fire-p02] Due to the length of the corresponding book, the third season only covered roughly the first half of *A Storm of Swords*.
[src:northwestern-university/a-song-of-ice-and-fire-p02] Early during the development of the TV series, Martin told major plot points to producers David Benioff and D.
[src:northwestern-university/a-song-of-ice-and-fire-p02] Martin was confident he would have published at least *The Winds of Winter* before the TV series overtook him.
[src:northwestern-university/a-song-of-ice-and-fire-p02] Nevertheless, there were general concerns about whether Martin would be able to stay ahead of the show.
[src:northwestern-university/a-song-of-ice-and-fire-p02] As a result, head writers Benioff and Weiss learned more future plot points from Martin in 2013 to help them set up the show's new possible seasons.
[src:northwestern-university/a-song-of-ice-and-fire-p02] This included the end stories for all the core characters.
[src:northwestern-university/a-song-of-ice-and-fire-p02] Deviations from the books' storylines were considered, but a two-year hiatus to wait for new books was not an option for them (as the child actors continue to grow and the show's popularity would wane).
[src:northwestern-university/a-song-of-ice-and-fire-p02] Shortly after the season 3 premiere in March 2013, the network renewed *Game of Thrones* for a fourth season, which would cover the second half of *A Storm of Swords*along with the beginnings of *A Feast for Crows*and *A Dance With Dragons*.
[src:northwestern-university/a-song-of-ice-and-fire-p02] *Game of Thrones* was nominated for 15 Emmy Awards for season 3.
[src:northwestern-university/a-song-of-ice-and-fire-p02] Two days after the fourth season premiered in April 2014, HBO renewed *Game of Thrones* for a fifth and sixth season.
[src:northwestern-university/a-song-of-ice-and-fire-p02] Season 5 premiered on April 12, 2015, and set a Guinness World Records for winning the highest number of Emmy Awards for a series in a single season and year, winning 12 out of 24 nominations, including Outstanding Drama Series.
[src:northwestern-university/a-song-of-ice-and-fire-p02] These episodes were watched by 8 million viewers, setting a record number for the series.
[src:northwestern-university/a-song-of-ice-and-fire-p02] On January 2, 2016, Martin confirmed that the sixth volume would not be published before the start of the sixth season of the HBO series.
[src:northwestern-university/a-song-of-ice-and-fire-p02] The sixth season premiered on April 24, 2016.
[src:northwestern-university/a-song-of-ice-and-fire-p02] These episodes received the most nominations for the 68th Primetime Emmy Awards with 23, winning 12, including the award for Outstanding Drama Series.
[src:northwestern-university/a-song-of-ice-and-fire-p02] The seventh season premiered on July 16, 2017.
[src:northwestern-university/a-song-of-ice-and-fire-p02] The eighth and final season premiered on April 14, 2019.
[src:northwestern-university/a-song-of-ice-and-fire-p02] A spin-off prequel television series, *House of the Dragon*, was later developed based on sections of Martin's *Fire & Blood* — specifically the second half of the first volume, an expanded version of the novellas *The Rogue Prince* and *The Princess and the Queen*.
[src:northwestern-university/a-song-of-ice-and-fire-p02] *House of the Dragon* is created by George R.
[src:northwestern-university/a-song-of-ice-and-fire-p02] It is the second television series in the *A Song of Ice and Fire* franchise.
[src:northwestern-university/a-song-of-ice-and-fire-p02] The series is set two hundred years before the events of *Game of Thrones* and chronicles the events leading up to the Targaryen civil war, known as the "Dance of the Dragons", and the war itself.
[src:northwestern-university/a-song-of-ice-and-fire-p02] *House of the Dragon* received a straight-to-series order in October 2019, with casting beginning in July 2020 and principal photography beginning in April 2021 in the United Kingdom.
[src:northwestern-university/a-song-of-ice-and-fire-p02] The first season of the series premiered in 2022 and consists of ten episodes, adapting "Heirs of the Dragon – A Question of Succession" from *Fire & Blood*, which focuses on the succession crisis following the deaths of Jaehaerys' sons and the eventual reign of his grandson Viserys I.
[src:northwestern-university/a-song-of-ice-and-fire-p02] The novella *The Rogue Prince*, previously published in the anthology *Rogues* in 2014, uses the majority of this text.
[src:northwestern-university/a-song-of-ice-and-fire-p02] Subsequent seasons adapt "The Dying of the Dragons" from *Fire & Blood*, which focuses on the Dance of the Dragons, the succession war between Rhaenyra Targaryen and her younger half-brother Aegon II, and forms the primary basis of *House of the Dragon*.
[src:northwestern-university/a-song-of-ice-and-fire-p02] An abridged version was included in the novella *The Princess and the Queen*, which was published in the anthology *Dangerous Women* in 2013.
[src:northwestern-university/a-song-of-ice-and-fire-p02] The second season premiered in 2024 and consists of eight episodes.
[src:northwestern-university/a-song-of-ice-and-fire-p02] Another spin-off prequel series, *A Knight of the Seven Kingdoms*, was developed based on Martin's *Tales of Dunk and Egg* novellas.
[src:northwestern-university/a-song-of-ice-and-fire-p02] *A Knight of the Seven Kingdoms* is created by George R.
[src:northwestern-university/a-song-of-ice-and-fire-p02] It is the third television series in the *A Song of Ice and Fire* franchise.
[src:northwestern-university/a-song-of-ice-and-fire-p02] It follows the adventures of "Dunk" (Ser Duncan the Tall, a hedge knight) and "Egg" (Prince Aegon Targaryen, the future King Aegon V), some 90 years before the events of the novels.
[src:northwestern-university/a-song-of-ice-and-fire-p02] It stars Peter Claffey as Dunk and Dexter Sol Ansell as Egg.
[src:northwestern-university/a-song-of-ice-and-fire-p02] The first season of the series premiered in 2026 and consists of six episodes, adapting the first novella, *The Hedge Knight*.
[src:northwestern-university/a-song-of-ice-and-fire-p02] On April 14, 2026, Warner Bros. announced at CinemaCon in Las Vegas that a feature film about Aegon's Conquest is in the works, based on the first chapters of Martin's *Fire & Blood*.
[src:northwestern-university/a-song-of-ice-and-fire-p02] The film is set to be written by Beau Willimon and is expected to be released in 2027 or later.
[src:northwestern-university/a-song-of-ice-and-fire-p02] The working title *Game of Thrones: Aegon's Conquest* was also confirmed.
[src:northwestern-university/act-test] The **ACT** (/ˈeɪ.ˌsiː.ˌtiː/ ⓘ, *AY-see-tee*; originally an abbreviation of **American College Testing**) is a standardized test used for college admissions in the United States.
[src:northwestern-university/act-test] It is administered by ACT, Inc., a for-profit organization of the same name.
[src:northwestern-university/act-test] The ACT test covers three academic skill areas: English, mathematics, and reading.
[src:northwestern-university/act-test] It also offers optional scientific reasoning and direct writing tests.
[src:northwestern-university/act-test] It is accepted by many four-year colleges and universities in the United States as well as more than 225 universities outside of the U.S.
[src:northwestern-university/act-test] The multiple-choice test sections of the ACT (all except the optional writing test) are individually scored on a scale of 1–36.
[src:northwestern-university/act-test] In addition, a composite score consisting of the rounded whole number average of the scores for English, reading, and math is provided.
[src:northwestern-university/act-test] The ACT was first introduced in November 1959 by University of Iowa professor Everett Franklin Lindquist as a competitor to the SAT.
[src:northwestern-university/act-test] The ACT originally consisted of four tests: English, Mathematics, Social Studies, and Natural Sciences.
[src:northwestern-university/act-test] In 1989, however, the Social Studies test was changed into a Reading section (which included a social sciences subsection), and the Natural Sciences test was renamed the Science Reasoning test, with more emphasis on problem-solving skills as opposed to memorizing scientific facts.
[src:northwestern-university/act-test] In February 2005, an optional Writing Test was added to the ACT.
[src:northwestern-university/act-test] By the fall of 2017, computer-based ACT tests were available for school-day testing in limited school districts of the US, with greater availability expected in fall of 2018.
[src:northwestern-university/act-test] In July 2024, the ACT announced that the test duration was shortened; the science section, like the writing one, would become optional; and online testing would be rolled out nationally in spring 2025 and for school-day testing in spring 2026.
[src:northwestern-university/act-test] The ACT has seen a gradual increase in the number of test takers since its inception, and in 2012 the ACT surpassed the SAT for the first time in total test takers; that year, 1,666,017 students took the ACT and 1,664,479 students took the SAT.
[src:northwestern-university/act-test] On June 30th, 2026, ETS, the largest educational testing and assessment nonprofit, announced the acquisition of ACT.
[src:northwestern-university/act-test] ACT, Inc., says that the ACT assessment measures high school students' general educational development and their capability to complete college-level work with the multiple choice tests covering four skill areas: English, mathematics, reading, and (optionally) science.
[src:northwestern-university/act-test] The optional Writing Test measures skill in planning and writing a short essay.
[src:northwestern-university/act-test] Specifically, ACT states that its scores provide an indicator of "college readiness", and that scores in each of the subtests correspond to skills in entry-level college courses in English, algebra, social science, humanities, and biology.
[src:northwestern-university/act-test] According to a research study conducted by ACT, Inc. in 2003, there was a relationship between a student's ACT composite score and the probability of that student earning a college degree.
[src:northwestern-university/act-test] To develop the test, ACT incorporates the objectives for instruction from middle and high schools throughout the United States, reviews approved textbooks for subjects taught in Grades 7–12, and surveys educators on which knowledge skills are relevant to success in postsecondary education.
[src:northwestern-university/act-test] ACT publishes a technical manual that summarizes studies conducted on its validity in predicting freshman GPA, equating different high school GPAs, and measuring educational achievement.
[src:northwestern-university/act-test] ACT scores are used to supplement the secondary school record and help admission officers put local data—such as coursework, grades, and class rank—in a national perspective.
[src:northwestern-university/act-test] The majority of colleges do not indicate a preference for the SAT or ACT exams and accept both, being treated equally by most admissions officers.
[src:northwestern-university/act-test] Most colleges use ACT scores as only one factor in the admission process.
[src:northwestern-university/act-test] A sampling of ACT admissions scores shows that the 75th percentile composite score was 24.1 at public four-year institutions and 25.3 at private four-year institutions.
[src:northwestern-university/act-test] In addition, some states and individual school districts have used the ACT to assess student learning and/or the performance of schools, requiring all high school students to take the ACT, regardless of whether they are college bound.
[src:northwestern-university/act-test] Colorado and Illinois were the first to incorporate the ACT as part of their mandatory testing program in 2001.
[src:northwestern-university/act-test] Other states followed suit in subsequent years.
[src:northwestern-university/act-test] During the 2018–2019 school year, 13 states will administer the ACT test to all public school 11th graders, and another six states will fund ACT test administration as an option or choice for districts.
[src:northwestern-university/act-test] The ACT is more widely used in the Midwestern, Rocky Mountain, and Southern United States, whereas the SAT is more popular on the East and West coasts.
[src:northwestern-university/act-test] Recently, however, the ACT is being used more on the East Coast.
[src:northwestern-university/act-test] Use of the ACT by colleges has risen as a result of various criticisms of the effectiveness and fairness of the SAT.
[src:northwestern-university/act-test] The required portion of the ACT is divided into three multiple-choice subject tests: English, mathematics, and reading.
[src:northwestern-university/act-test] Subject test scores, including the optional science section, range from 1 to 36; all scores are integers.
[src:northwestern-university/act-test] The English, mathematics, and reading tests also have subscores ranging from 1 to 18 (the subject score is not the sum of the subscores).
[src:northwestern-university/act-test] In addition, students taking the optional writing test receive a writing score ranging from 2 to 12 (this is a change from the previous 1–36 score range); the optional science and writing scores do not affect the composite score.
[src:northwestern-university/act-test] Prior to September 2015, there was a Combined English/Writing score, which was a 36-point combination of the 36-point English Test score and the 12-point Writing subscore.
[src:northwestern-university/act-test] The ACT has eliminated the Combined English/writing score and has added two new combined scores: ELA (an average of the English, Reading, and Writing scores) and STEM (an average of the Math and Science scores).
[src:northwestern-university/act-test] These changes for the writing, ELA, and STEM scores were effective starting with the September 2015 test.
[src:northwestern-university/act-test] Each question answered correctly is worth one raw point, and there is no penalty for marking incorrect answers on the multiple-choice parts of the test; a student can answer all questions without a decrease in their score due to incorrect answers.
[src:northwestern-university/act-test] This is parallel to several AP Tests eliminating the penalties for incorrect answers.
[src:northwestern-university/act-test] To improve the result, students can retake the test: 55% of students who retake the ACT improve their scores, 22% score the same, and 23% see their scores decrease.
[src:northwestern-university/act-test] The first section is the 45-minute English test covering usage/mechanics, sentence structure, and rhetorical skills.
[src:northwestern-university/act-test] The 75-question test consists of five passages with various sections underlined on one side of the page and options to correct the underlined portions on the other side of the page.
[src:northwestern-university/act-test] The second section is a 60-minute, 60-question math test with the usual distribution of questions being approximately 14 covering pre-algebra, 10 elementary algebra, 9 intermediate algebra, 14 plane geometry, 9 coordinate geometry, and 4 elementary trigonometry questions.
[src:northwestern-university/act-test] However, the distribution of question topics varies from test to test.
[src:northwestern-university/act-test] The difficulty of questions usually increases as a test taker moves on to higher question numbers.
[src:northwestern-university/act-test] Calculators are permitted in this section only.
[src:northwestern-university/act-test] Standard graphing calculators, such as the TI-83 and TI-84, are allowed.
[src:northwestern-university/act-test] Within the TI-Nspire family, the standard and CX versions are allowed while the CX CAS is not.
[src:northwestern-university/act-test] As of April 2025 for online tests, and September 2025 for paper-and-pencil tests, each math question has four answer choices instead of five.
[src:northwestern-university/act-test] The reading section is a 35-minute, 40-question test that consists of four sections, three of which contain one long prose passage and one which contains two shorter prose passages.
[src:northwestern-university/act-test] The passages are representative of the levels and kinds of text commonly encountered in first-year college curriculum.
[src:northwestern-university/act-test] This reading test assesses skills in three general categories: key ideas and details, craft and structure, and integration of knowledge and ideas.
[src:northwestern-university/act-test] Test questions will usually ask students to derive meaning from texts referring to what is explicitly stated or by reasoning to determine implicit meanings.
[src:northwestern-university/act-test] The optional science section is a 35-minute, 40-question test.
[src:northwestern-university/act-test] There are seven passages each followed by five to seven questions.
[src:northwestern-university/act-test] The passages have three different formats: Data Representation, Research Summary, and Conflicting Viewpoints.
[src:northwestern-university/act-test] But so far, there is still always only one Conflicting Viewpoints passage.
[src:northwestern-university/act-test] These changes are very recent, and the only reference to them so far is in the recently released practice test on the ACT website.
[src:northwestern-university/act-test] The science section was mandatory until 2024, when it was made optional with the goal of giving students additional flexibility when taking the ACT exam.
[src:northwestern-university/act-test] The optional writing section, which is always administered at the end of the test, is 40 minutes (increasing from the original 30-minute time limit on the September 2015 test).
[src:northwestern-university/act-test] The essay does not affect the composite score or the English section score; it is only given as a separate writing score and is included in the ELA score.
[src:northwestern-university/act-test] Two trained readers assign each essay subscores between 1 and 6 in four different categories: Ideas and Analysis, Development and Support, Organization, Language Use and Conventions.
[src:northwestern-university/act-test] Scores of 0 are reserved for essays that are blank, off-topic, non-English, not written with a no.
[src:northwestern-university/act-test] 2 pencil, or considered illegible after several attempts at reading.
[src:northwestern-university/act-test] The subscores from the two different readers are summed to produce final domain scores from 2 to 12 (or 0) in each of the four categories.
[src:northwestern-university/act-test] If the two readers' subscores differ by more than one point, then a senior third reader makes the final decision on the score.
[src:northwestern-university/act-test] The four domain scores are combined through a process that has not been described to create a writing section score between 1 and 36.
[src:northwestern-university/act-test] Note that the domain scores are not added to create the writing section score.
[src:northwestern-university/act-test] Although the writing section is optional, many colleges require an essay score and will factor it into the admissions decision (but fewer than half of all colleges have this requirement).
[src:northwestern-university/act-test] For the "enhanced" version of the ACT introduced in 1989, the mean score of each of the four tests, as well as the mean composite score, was scaled to be 18, with an intended standard error of measurement of 2 for the four test scores and 1 for the composite score.
[src:northwestern-university/act-test] These statistics vary from year to year for current populations of ACT takers.
[src:northwestern-university/act-test] The chart below summarizes each section and the average test score based on graduating high school seniors in 2025.
[src:northwestern-university/act-test] The table below summarizes how many students achieved a composite score of 36 on the ACT between the years of 1990 and 2025.
[src:northwestern-university/act-test] The ACT Assessment Student Report, at ACT.org, provides the typical ACT Composite averages for college and universities admission policies.
[src:northwestern-university/act-test] They caution that "because admission policies vary across colleges, the score ranges should be considered rough guidelines." Following is a list of the average composite scores that typically are accepted at colleges or universities.
[src:northwestern-university/act-test] The ACT is offered seven times a year in the United States and its territories, Puerto Rico, and Canada: in September, October, December, February, April, June, and July.
[src:northwestern-university/act-test] (In New York State, the test is not offered in July.) In other locations, the ACT is offered five times a year: in September, October, December, April, and June.
[src:northwestern-university/act-test] The ACT is offered only on Saturdays except for those with credible religious obligations, who may take the test on another day.
[src:northwestern-university/act-test] The ACT is designed, administered, and scored so that there is no advantage to testing on one particular date.
[src:northwestern-university/act-test] For candidates in the United States, the ACT assessment costs $65.00 and there are two optional add-ons, the science section ($4.00) and the writing section ($25.00).
[src:northwestern-university/act-test] For candidates outside of the United States, the test costs considerably more, at $186.50, with science costing $10.00, although writing retains its price of $25.00.
[src:northwestern-university/act-test] For the 2025 testing dates, the science section is only optional for the digital test.
[src:northwestern-university/act-test] Students with verifiable disabilities, including physical and learning disabilities, are eligible to take the test with accommodations.
[src:northwestern-university/act-test] The standard time increase for students requiring additional time due to disabilities is 50%.
[src:northwestern-university/act-test] Originally, the score sheet was labeled that additional time was granted due to a learning disability; however, this was ultimately dropped because it was deemed illegal under the Americans with Disabilities Act and could be perceived as an unfair designator of disability.
[src:northwestern-university/act-test] Scores are sent to the student, their high school, and up to four colleges of the student's choice (optional).
[src:northwestern-university/act-test] Time is a major factor to consider in testing.
[src:northwestern-university/act-test] The ACT is generally regarded as being composed of somewhat easier questions versus the SAT, but the shorter time allotted to complete each section increases difficulty.
[src:northwestern-university/act-test] Comparatively, the SAT is structured such that the test taker is allowed at least one minute per question, on generally shorter sections (25 or fewer questions).
[src:northwestern-university/act-test] Times may be adjusted as a matter of accommodation for certain disabilities or other impairments.
[src:northwestern-university/act-test] Score reports provided to students taking the ACT test include the ranks (or cumulative percents) for each score and subscore received by the student.
[src:northwestern-university/act-test] Each rank gives the percentage of recently tested students in the U.S. who scored at or below the given student's score.
[src:northwestern-university/act-test] The following table shows the ACT national ranks as of the 2020-21 school year.
[src:northwestern-university/act-test] The College Board (the developer of the SAT) and ACT, Inc. compared scores from about 600,000 students who were graduating in 2017 and who took both the SAT (2016 revision) and the ACT in 2016 and 2017.
[src:northwestern-university/act-test] The following table shows, for each ACT composite score in the data set, the corresponding range of SAT total scores for students with the same percentile rank on each test.
[src:northwestern-university/act-test] The most appropriate corresponding SAT score point for the given ACT score is also shown in the table.
[src:northwestern-university/act-test] The data in this section pertains to the SAT prior to the 2016 redesign.
[src:northwestern-university/act-test] Comparisons to SAT scores are not valid after the 2017 graduating class.
[src:northwestern-university/act-test] Sixty percent—about 2.03 million students—of the 2017 high school graduating class took the ACT.
[src:northwestern-university/act-test] For the graduating class of 2017, the average composite score was a 21.0.
[src:northwestern-university/act-test] Of these test-takers, 46% were male and 52% were female, with 2% not reporting a gender.
[src:northwestern-university/act-test] 2,760 students in the graduating class of 2017 received the highest ACT composite score of 36.
[src:northwestern-university/act-test] The following chart shows, for each ACT score from 11 to 36, the corresponding ACT percentile and equivalent total SAT score or score range.
[src:northwestern-university/act-test] (Concordance data for ACT scores less than 11 is not yet available for the current version of the SAT.) Note that ACT percentiles are defined as the percentage of test takers scoring at or below the given score.
[src:northwestern-university/aqr-capital] AQR employs a research-based "systematic and consistent approach" to portfolio construction.
[src:northwestern-university/aqr-capital] This disciplined approach of identifying long-term, repeatable sources of return means "having a high conviction in the process, but not a high conviction in any particular stock".
[src:northwestern-university/aqr-capital] The firm is a strong proponent of diversification within portfolios, as well as adding strategies with low correlation to traditional asset classes as a complement to existing portfolios.
[src:northwestern-university/aqr-capital] AQR was an early adopter of style, or factor, investing given the strategy's academic roots.
[src:northwestern-university/aqr-capital] Although the four styles — value, momentum, defensive and carry — have been well-known and used in quantitative investing for decades, AQR has long advocated for using these styles together, citing their diversifying qualities.
[src:northwestern-university/aqr-capital] AQR is perhaps best known for its alternative investment strategies, which aim to offer low correlation to traditional, equity-dominated portfolios.
[src:northwestern-university/aqr-capital] AQR was one of the first investment managers to offer a risk parity strategy, which aims to balance allocations based on underlying risk rather than asset classes.
[src:northwestern-university/aqr-capital] The firm also offers managed futures, a trend-following strategy that is “uncorrelated with other asset classes” and supported by over a century of academic evidence.
[src:northwestern-university/aqr-capital] AQR was one of the first investment management firms to offer alternative mutual funds, launching its family of mutual funds in 2009.
[src:northwestern-university/aqr-capital] The firm's liquid alternative strategies were a “category leader” in Morningstar’s ranking for 2015.
[src:northwestern-university/aqr-capital] Three of AQR's founding principals — Cliff Asness, Robert Krail and John Liew — met in the University of Chicago’s PhD program, where the foundation of the firm's investment philosophy took shape.
[src:northwestern-university/aqr-capital] While still working on his dissertation, which focused on momentum and value, Asness joined Goldman Sachs, where he was asked to lead a new quantitative research team within the firm's asset management division.
[src:northwestern-university/aqr-capital] Liew and Krail joined him, and the new team applied what they learned in academia to manage both hedge-fund and long-only assets.
[src:northwestern-university/aqr-capital] In 1998, Asness, David Kabiller, Krail and Liew left Goldman Sachs to establish AQR.
[src:northwestern-university/aqr-capital] AQR was among the first hedge fund managers to voluntarily register at its inception with the United States Securities and Exchange Commission.
[src:northwestern-university/aqr-capital] The firm's first product was a hedge fund, though it soon (2000) entered into traditional portfolio management.
[src:northwestern-university/aqr-capital] In 2001, AQR had nearly $750 million assets under management.
[src:northwestern-university/aqr-capital] In 2004, AQR had $12 billion assets under management.
[src:northwestern-university/aqr-capital] The firm opened its first international office in Australia in 2005.
[src:northwestern-university/aqr-capital] In 2009, AQR became one of the first investment managers to offer alternative mutual funds.
[src:northwestern-university/aqr-capital] In 2011, the firm opened an office in the UK.
[src:northwestern-university/aqr-capital] After AQR's annual profit plunged 34% in 2018, the firm announced job cuts in January 2019.
[src:northwestern-university/aqr-capital] As of Q3 2019, the firm had $185 billion in assets under management.
[src:northwestern-university/aqr-capital] As of 2016, approximately half of the AQR's employees have earned advanced degrees, with 52 holding PhDs.
[src:northwestern-university/aqr-capital] In 2015, AQR established QUANTA Academy, the firm's learning and development program, which is focused on three core pillars: Technical Skills and Knowledge, Leadership and Management, and Personal Enrichment.
[src:northwestern-university/aqr-capital] With a focus on lifelong learning, the program is designed to help employees reach their full potential through hundreds of courses annually.
[src:northwestern-university/aqr-capital] AQR's Insight Award (see below), which “recognizes the most significant and innovative academic research that offers practical applications for investors,” awarded its fifth annual slate of winners in 2016.
[src:northwestern-university/aqr-capital] In 2014, AQR partnered with the London Business School to establish The AQR Asset Management Institute, which focuses on asset management research and thought leadership.
[src:northwestern-university/aqr-capital] The Institute rewards scholars in the field with annual grants and prizes.
[src:northwestern-university/aqr-capital] AQR donated more than $15 million to be spread out over ten years.
[src:northwestern-university/aqr-capital] The firm is also a sponsor of the AQR Top Finance Graduate Award at Copenhagen Business School, which honors the PhD graduates whose research carries the greatest potential impact.
[src:northwestern-university/northwestern-university-p01] Northwestern is composed of eleven undergraduate, graduate, and professional schools in the fields of management, law, journalism, engineering, medicine, and others.
[src:northwestern-university/northwestern-university-p01] As of 2024, the university had an endowment of $15.6 billion, an annual budget of around $3.3 billion, and research funding of over $1 billion.
[src:northwestern-university/northwestern-university-p01] The university fields 19 intercollegiate athletic teams, the Northwestern Wildcats, which compete in the NCAA Division I in the Big Ten Conference.
[src:northwestern-university/northwestern-university-p01] As of September 2020, 37 Nobel Prize laureates and 2 Fields Medalists were affiliated with Northwestern as alumni or faculty.
[src:northwestern-university/northwestern-university-p01] In addition, Northwestern has been associated with 47 Pulitzer Prize winners, 23 National Medal of Science winners, 11 National Humanities Medal recipients, 23 MacArthur Fellows, 20 Rhodes Scholars, and 28 Marshall Scholars.
[src:northwestern-university/northwestern-university-p01] Northwestern alumni also include 10 living billionaires, 2 U.S.
[src:northwestern-university/northwestern-university-p01] Supreme Court justices, and 25 Olympic medalists.
[src:northwestern-university/northwestern-university-p01] The foundation of Northwestern University can be traced to a meeting on May 31, 1850, of nine prominent Chicago businessmen, Methodist leaders, and attorneys who had formed the idea of establishing a university to serve what had been known from 1787 to 1803 as the Northwest Territory.
[src:northwestern-university/northwestern-university-p01] On January 28, 1851, the Illinois General Assembly granted a charter to the *Trustees of the North-Western University*, making it the first chartered university in Illinois.
[src:northwestern-university/northwestern-university-p01] The school's nine founders, all of whom were Methodists (three of them ministers), knelt in prayer and worship before launching their first organizational meeting.
[src:northwestern-university/northwestern-university-p01] Although they affiliated the university with the Methodist Episcopal Church, they favored a non-sectarian admissions policy, believing that Northwestern should serve all people in the newly developing territory by bettering the economy in Evanston.
[src:northwestern-university/northwestern-university-p01] John Evans, for whom Evanston is named, bought 379 acres (153 ha) of land along Lake Michigan in 1853, and Philo Judson developed plans for what would become the city of Evanston, Illinois.
[src:northwestern-university/northwestern-university-p01] The first building, Old College, opened on November 5, 1855.
[src:northwestern-university/northwestern-university-p01] To raise funds for its construction, Northwestern sold $100 "perpetual scholarships" entitling the purchaser and his heirs to free tuition.
[src:northwestern-university/northwestern-university-p01] Another building, University Hall, was built in 1869 of the same Joliet limestone as the Chicago Water Tower, also built in 1869, one of the few buildings in the heart of Chicago to survive the Great Chicago Fire of 1871.
[src:northwestern-university/northwestern-university-p01] In 1873 Evanston College for Ladies merged with Northwestern.
[src:northwestern-university/northwestern-university-p01] Frances Willard, who later gained fame as a suffragette and as one of the founders of the Woman's Christian Temperance Union, became the school's first dean of women (Willard Residential College, built in 1938, honors her name).
[src:northwestern-university/northwestern-university-p01] Northwestern admitted its first female students in 1869, and the first woman graduated in 1874.
[src:northwestern-university/northwestern-university-p01] Northwestern fielded its first intercollegiate football team in 1882, later becoming a founding member of the Big Ten Conference.
[src:northwestern-university/northwestern-university-p01] In the 1870s and 1880s, Northwestern affiliated itself with already existing schools of law, medicine, and dentistry in Chicago.
[src:northwestern-university/northwestern-university-p01] As the university's enrollments grew, these professional schools were integrated with the undergraduate college in Evanston.
[src:northwestern-university/northwestern-university-p01] The result was a modern research university combining professional, graduate, and undergraduate programs, which gave equal weight to teaching and research.
[src:northwestern-university/northwestern-university-p01] By the turn of the century, Northwestern had grown in stature to become the third-largest university in the United States after Harvard University and the University of Michigan.
[src:northwestern-university/northwestern-university-p01] Under Walter Dill Scott's presidency from 1920 to 1939, Northwestern began construction of an integrated campus in Chicago designed by James Gamble Rogers, noted for his Collegiate Gothic architecture, to house the professional schools.
[src:northwestern-university/northwestern-university-p01] In addition, James Gamble Rogers designed a library in accordance with the gothic architectural style on the Evanston campus in order to make use of the $1 million donated to the school after the death of Charles Deering.
[src:northwestern-university/northwestern-university-p01] This library is named in memory of him and its design was inspired by Cambridge University's King's College Chapel.
[src:northwestern-university/northwestern-university-p01] The university also established the Kellogg School of Management and built several prominent buildings on the Evanston campus, including Dyche Stadium, now named Ryan Field, among others.
[src:northwestern-university/northwestern-university-p01] In the 1920s, Northwestern became one of the first six universities in the United States to establish a Naval Reserve Officers Training Corps (NROTC).
[src:northwestern-university/northwestern-university-p01] In 1939, Northwestern hosted the first-ever NCAA Division I men's basketball championship game in the original Patten Gymnasium, which was later demolished and relocated farther north, along with the Dearborn Observatory, to make room for the Technological Institute.
[src:northwestern-university/northwestern-university-p01] After the golden years of the 1920s, the Great Depression in the United States (1929–1941) had a severe impact on the university's finances.
[src:northwestern-university/northwestern-university-p01] Its annual income dropped 25 percent from $4.8 million in 1930–31 to $3.6 million in 1933–34.
[src:northwestern-university/northwestern-university-p01] Investment income shrank, fewer people could pay full tuition, and annual giving from alumni and philanthropists fell from $870,000 in 1932 to a low of $331,000 in 1935.
[src:northwestern-university/northwestern-university-p01] The university responded with two salary cuts of 10 percent each for all employees.
[src:northwestern-university/northwestern-university-p01] It imposed hiring and building freezes and slashed appropriations for maintenance, books, and research.
[src:northwestern-university/northwestern-university-p01] Having had a balanced budget in 1930–31, the university now faced deficits of roughly $100,000 for the next four years.
[src:northwestern-university/northwestern-university-p01] Enrollments fell in most schools, with law and music suffering the biggest declines.
[src:northwestern-university/northwestern-university-p01] However, the movement toward state certification of school teachers prompted Northwestern to start a new graduate program in education, thereby bringing in new students and much-needed income.
[src:northwestern-university/northwestern-university-p01] In June 1933, Robert Maynard Hutchins, president of the University of Chicago, proposed a merger of the two universities, estimating annual savings of $1.7 million.
[src:northwestern-university/northwestern-university-p01] The two presidents were enthusiastic, and the faculty liked the idea; many Northwestern alumni, however, opposed it, fearing the loss of their alma mater and its many traditions that distinguished Northwestern from Chicago.
[src:northwestern-university/northwestern-university-p01] The medical school, for example, was oriented toward training practitioners, and alumni feared it would lose its mission if it were merged into the more research-oriented University of Chicago Medical School.
[src:northwestern-university/northwestern-university-p01] In 1935, the Deering family rescued the university budget with an unrestricted gift of $6 million, bringing the budget up to $5.4 million in 1938–39.
[src:northwestern-university/northwestern-university-p01] This allowed many of the previous spending cuts to be restored, including half of the salary reductions.
[src:northwestern-university/northwestern-university-p01] Like other American universities, Northwestern was transformed by World War II (1939–1945).
[src:northwestern-university/northwestern-university-p01] Regular enrollment fell dramatically, but the school opened high-intensity, short-term programs that trained over 50,000 military personnel, including future president John F.
[src:northwestern-university/northwestern-university-p01] Northwestern's existing NROTC program proved to be a boon to the university as it trained over 36,000 sailors over the course of the war, which led Northwestern to be called the "Annapolis of the Midwest." Franklyn B.
[src:northwestern-university/northwestern-university-p01] Snyder led the university from 1939 to 1949, and after the war, surging enrollments under the G.I.
[src:northwestern-university/northwestern-university-p01] Bill drove the dramatic expansion of both campuses.
[src:northwestern-university/northwestern-university-p01] In 1948, prominent anthropologist Melville J.
[src:northwestern-university/northwestern-university-p01] Herskovits founded the Program of African Studies at Northwestern, the first center of its kind at an American academic institution.
[src:northwestern-university/northwestern-university-p01] Roscoe Miller's tenure as president from 1949 to 1970 saw an expansion of the Evanston campus, with the construction of the Lakefill on Lake Michigan, growth of the faculty and new academic programs, and polarizing Vietnam-era student protests.
[src:northwestern-university/northwestern-university-p01] In 1978, the first and second Unabomber attacks occurred at Northwestern University.
[src:northwestern-university/northwestern-university-p01] Relations between Evanston and Northwestern became strained throughout much of the post-war era because of episodes of disruptive student activism, disputes over municipal zoning, building codes, and law enforcement, as well as restrictions on the sale of alcohol near campus until 1972.
[src:northwestern-university/northwestern-university-p01] Northwestern's exemption from state and municipal property-tax obligations under its original charter has historically been a source of town-and-gown tension.
[src:northwestern-university/northwestern-university-p01] Although government support for universities declined in the 1970s and 1980s, President Arnold R.
[src:northwestern-university/northwestern-university-p01] Weber was able to stabilize university finances, which led to a revitalization of its campuses.
[src:northwestern-university/northwestern-university-p01] In 1996, Diana, Princess of Wales visited Northwestern's Evanston and Chicago campuses to raise money for the university hospital's Robert H.
[src:northwestern-university/northwestern-university-p01] Lurie Comprehensive Cancer Center at the invitation of then-President Henry Bienen.
[src:northwestern-university/northwestern-university-p01] Her visit raised a total of $1.5 million for cancer research.
[src:northwestern-university/northwestern-university-p01] As admissions to colleges and universities grew increasingly competitive in the 1990s and 2000s, President Bienen's tenure saw an increase in the number and quality of undergraduate applicants, continued expansion of the facilities and faculty, and renewed athletic competitiveness.
[src:northwestern-university/northwestern-university-p01] In the 2010s, a five-year capital campaign resulted in a new music center, a replacement building for the business school, and a $270 million athletic complex.
[src:northwestern-university/northwestern-university-p01] In 2014, President Barack Obama delivered a seminal economics speech at the Evanston campus.
[src:northwestern-university/northwestern-university-p01] In 2015, Queen Máxima and King Willem-Alexander of the Netherlands visited Northwestern to announce research collaborations between Northwestern and several Dutch institutions focused on the study of aging.
[src:northwestern-university/northwestern-university-p01] In 2021, an additional $480 million, the largest donation in the university's history, was donated to Northwestern by the Ryan Family to be applied to research at the Kellogg School of Management and Feinberg School of Medicine, as well as for renovating Ryan Field.
[src:northwestern-university/northwestern-university-p01] In a partnership with Oakton College and the Illinois Department of Corrections in 2023, Northwestern became the first top-ranked university in the United States to award bachelor's degrees to a graduating class of prisoners.
[src:northwestern-university/northwestern-university-p01] In April 2024, Northwestern University students joined other campuses across the United States in protests against the Gaza war.
[src:northwestern-university/northwestern-university-p01] The student protestors demanded divestment from companies with ties to Israel and that the administration protect freedom of speech, civil rights and be transparent with their investments moving forward.
[src:northwestern-university/northwestern-university-p01] The university administration came to an agreement with the protestors, now known as the Deering Meadow agreement, which permitted peaceful demonstrations, gave students representation on an investment committee and pledged to bring Palestinian students to campus.
[src:northwestern-university/northwestern-university-p01] In February 2025, Leo Terrell, the head of the Trump administration's Task Force to Combat Antisemitism, announced that he would investigate Northwestern University as part of the Department of Justice's broader investigation into antisemitism on college campuses.
[src:northwestern-university/northwestern-university-p01] On November 29, 2025, Northwestern University announced that it had reached an agreement with the Trump administration to restore hundreds of millions of dollars in federal research funding that had been frozen amid investigations into alleged antisemitism and civil rights violations.
[src:northwestern-university/northwestern-university-p01] Under the deal, the university will pay the federal government $75 million over three years and implement changes to student conduct policies, and federal investigations into the school will be ended; the university stated that the settlement does not constitute an admission of wrongdoing.
[src:northwestern-university/northwestern-university-p01] Northwestern University also agreed to several political demands by the Trump administration, including to implement certain anti-transgender policies.
[src:northwestern-university/northwestern-university-p01] The university also agreed to terminate the 2024 Deering Meadow agreement they had previously negotiated with pro- Palestinian student activists.
[src:northwestern-university/northwestern-university-p01] On May 18, 2026, Mung Chiang was named as the new president, and will assume the role in June 2026.
[src:northwestern-university/northwestern-university-p01] Northwestern's main campus is on the shore of Lake Michigan in the Chicago metropolitan area.
[src:northwestern-university/northwestern-university-p01] The campus spans an area of 240 acres and is characterized by its blend of modern and historic gothic architecture.
[src:northwestern-university/northwestern-university-p01] Northwestern's Evanston campus, where the undergraduate schools, the Graduate School, and the Kellogg School of Management are located, runs north–south from Lincoln Avenue to Clark Street west of Lake Michigan along Sheridan Road.
[src:northwestern-university/northwestern-university-p01] North Campus is home to the fraternity quads, athletics facilities including the Henry Crown Sports Pavilion and Norris Aquatics Center, the Technological Institute, Dearborn Observatory, the Patrick G. and Shirley W.
[src:northwestern-university/northwestern-university-p01] Ryan Hall for Nanofabrication and Molecular Self-Assembly, and the Ford Motor Company Engineering Design Center among others.
[src:northwestern-university/northwestern-university-p01] South Campus is home to the university's humanities buildings, music buildings like the Pick-Staiger Concert Hall, the Mary and Leigh Block Museum of Art, and the sorority quads.
[src:northwestern-university/northwestern-university-p01] In the 1960s, the university created an additional 84 acres (34 ha) for the campus by filling in a portion of Lake Michigan.
[src:northwestern-university/northwestern-university-p01] Buildings located on the resulting Lakefill include University Library, the Patrick G. and Shirley W.
[src:northwestern-university/northwestern-university-p01] Ryan Center for the Musical Arts, the Regenstein Hall of Music, Norris University Center (the student union), the Kellogg School of Management Global Hub, and various athletics facilities.
[src:northwestern-university/northwestern-university-p01] The Chicago Transit Authority's elevated train running through Evanston is called the Purple Line, taking its name from Northwestern's school color.
[src:northwestern-university/northwestern-university-p01] The Foster and Davis stations are within walking distance of the southern end of the campus, while the Noyes station is close to the northern end of the campus.
[src:northwestern-university/northwestern-university-p01] The Central station is close to Ryan Field, Northwestern's football stadium.
[src:northwestern-university/northwestern-university-p01] The Evanston Davis Street station serves the Northwestern campus in downtown Evanston and the Evanston Central Street station is near Ryan Field.
[src:northwestern-university/northwestern-university-p01] Pace Suburban Bus Service and the CTA have several bus routes that run through or near the Evanston campus.
[src:northwestern-university/northwestern-university-p01] Northwestern's Chicago campus is located in the city's Streeterville neighborhood near Lake Michigan.
[src:northwestern-university/northwestern-university-p01] The Chicago campus is home to the nationally ranked Northwestern Memorial Hospital, the medical school, the law school, the part-time MBA program, and the School of Professional Studies.
[src:northwestern-university/northwestern-university-p01] Medill's one-year graduate program rents a floor on Wacker Drive, across the river from Streeterville and separate from the rest of the campus.
[src:northwestern-university/northwestern-university-p01] Northwestern's professional schools and a number of its affiliated hospitals are located approximately four blocks east of the Chicago station on the CTA Red Line.
[src:northwestern-university/northwestern-university-p01] The Chicago campus is also served by CTA bus routes.
[src:northwestern-university/northwestern-university-p01] Founded or affiliated at varying points in the university's history, the professional schools originally were scattered throughout Chicago.
[src:northwestern-university/northwestern-university-p01] In connection with a 1917 master plan for a central Chicago campus and President Walter Dill Scott's capital campaign, 8.5 acres (3.44 ha) of land were purchased at the corner of Chicago Avenue and Lake Shore Drive for $1.5 million in 1920.
[src:northwestern-university/northwestern-university-p01] Architect James Gamble Rogers was commissioned to create a master plan for the principal buildings on the new campus, which he designed in collegiate gothic style.
[src:northwestern-university/northwestern-university-p01] Montgomery Ward donated $8 million to the campaign to finance the construction of the Montgomery Ward Memorial Building, which would house the medical and dental schools, and create endowments for faculty chairs, research grants, scholarships, and building maintenance.
[src:northwestern-university/northwestern-university-p01] The building would become the first university skyscraper in the United States.
[src:northwestern-university/northwestern-university-p01] In addition to the Ward Building, Rogers designed Wieboldt Hall to house facilities for the School of Commerce and Levy Mayer Hall to house the School of Law.
[src:northwestern-university/northwestern-university-p01] The new campus comprising these three new buildings was dedicated during a two-day ceremony in June 1927.
[src:northwestern-university/northwestern-university-p01] The Chicago campus continued to expand with the addition of Thorne Hall in 1931 and Abbott Hall in 1939.
[src:northwestern-university/northwestern-university-p01] In October 2013, Northwestern began the demolition of the architecturally significant Prentice Women's Hospital.
[src:northwestern-university/northwestern-university-p01] Neilson, dean of the medical school, penned an op-ed that equated retaining the building with loss of life.
[src:northwestern-university/northwestern-university-p01] In Fall 2008, Northwestern opened a campus in Education City, Doha, Qatar.
[src:northwestern-university/northwestern-university-p01] Through the Medill School of Journalism and School of Communication, NU-Q offers bachelor's degrees in journalism and communications respectively.
[src:northwestern-university/northwestern-university-p01] However, some have questioned whether NU-Q can truly offer a comparable journalism program to that of its U.S. campus given Qatar's instances of censorship and strict limits on journalistic and academic freedoms.
[src:northwestern-university/northwestern-university-p01] Northwestern receives roughly $45 million per year to operate the campus.
[src:northwestern-university/northwestern-university-p01] In February 2016, Northwestern reached an agreement with the Qatar Foundation to extend the operations of the NU-Q branch for an additional decade, through the 2027–2028 academic year.
[src:northwestern-university/northwestern-university-p01] Northwestern is privately owned and governed by an appointed board of trustees composed of 70 members.
[src:northwestern-university/northwestern-university-p01] The board delegates its power to an elected president who serves as the chief executive officer of the university.
[src:northwestern-university/northwestern-university-p01] Northwestern has had seventeen presidents in its history (excluding interim presidents).
[src:northwestern-university/northwestern-university-p01] The former president, legal scholar Michael Schill, succeeded Morton O.
[src:northwestern-university/northwestern-university-p01] The president maintains a staff of vice presidents, directors, and other assistants for administrative, financial, faculty, and student matters.
[src:northwestern-university/northwestern-university-p01] Kathleen Haggerty assumed the role of provost for the university on September 1, 2020.
[src:northwestern-university/northwestern-university-p01] Students are formally involved in the university's administration through the Associated Student Government, elected representatives of the undergraduate students, and the Graduate Student Association, which represents the university's graduate students.
[src:northwestern-university/northwestern-university-p01] The admission requirements, degree requirements, courses of study, and disciplinary and degree recommendations for each of Northwestern's 12 schools are determined by the voting members of that school's faculty (assistant professor and above).
[src:northwestern-university/northwestern-university-p01] Northwestern maintains an endowment of $14.3 billion, the eighth-largest university endowment among private universities in the United States.
[src:northwestern-university/northwestern-university-p01] The endowment is sustained through donations and is maintained by investment advisers at the university's Investment Office.
[src:northwestern-university/northwestern-university-p01] Northwestern University's admissions are characterized as "most selective" by *U.S.
[src:northwestern-university/northwestern-university-p01] Northwestern received a record 52,225 applications for its class size of approximately 2,100 students in 2022–2023 academic year.
[src:northwestern-university/northwestern-university-p01] For the Class of 2027, regular decision acceptance rate was approximately 4.6%, while overall acceptance rate remained around 7.0%.
[src:northwestern-university/northwestern-university-p01] ACT composite scores for the middle 50% ranged from 33 to 35 out of 36, and 96% ranked in the top ten percent of their respective high school classes.
[src:northwestern-university/northwestern-university-p01] Approximately 35–40% percent of the incoming students of the Class of 2027 have been admitted through the Early Decision application round.
[src:northwestern-university/northwestern-university-p01] Northwestern's early decision admission numbers for the Class of 2027 had an early acceptance rate of about 20%, with approximately 1,000 students being admitted out of 5,220 applications.
[src:northwestern-university/northwestern-university-p01] In April 2016, Northwestern became one of 15 Illinois universities to sign on to the Chicago Star Partnership, a City Colleges initiative aimed at increasing opportunities for students in the city's public school district.
[src:northwestern-university/northwestern-university-p01] The university is need-blind for domestic applicants.
[src:northwestern-university/northwestern-university-p01] Northwestern is a large, residential research university.
[src:northwestern-university/northwestern-university-p01] The university provides instruction in over 200 formal academic concentrations, 124 undergraduate programs, and 145 graduate and professional programs, including various dual degree programs.
[src:northwestern-university/northwestern-university-p01] Although there is no university-wide core curriculum, a foundation in the liberal arts and sciences, sometimes referred as distribution requirements, are required for all majors; individual degree requirements are set by the faculty of each school.
[src:northwestern-university/northwestern-university-p01] The university heavily emphasizes interdisciplinary learning, with 72% of undergrads combining two or more areas of study.
[src:northwestern-university/northwestern-university-p01] Northwestern's full-time undergraduate and graduate programs operate on an approximately 10-week academic quarter system with the academic year beginning in late September and ending in early June.
[src:northwestern-university/northwestern-university-p01] Under the regular academic calendar, each quarter contains a four-day Reading Period in between the end of classes and the beginning of finals.
[src:northwestern-university/northwestern-university-p01] Undergraduates typically take four courses each quarter and twelve courses in an academic year and are required to complete at least twelve quarters on campus to graduate.
[src:northwestern-university/northwestern-university-p01] Northwestern offers honors, accelerated, and joint degree programs in medicine, science, mathematics, engineering, and journalism.
[src:northwestern-university/northwestern-university-p01] The comprehensive doctoral graduate program has high coexistence with undergraduate programs.
[src:northwestern-university/northwestern-university-p01] The most popular and prominent majors at Northwestern in 2021 include communication, journalism, engineering, computer science, mathematics, statistics, biological sciences, physics, and chemistry.
[src:northwestern-university/northwestern-university-p01] It is also prominent in law and medicine.
[src:northwestern-university/northwestern-university-p01] Northwestern is accredited by the Higher Learning Commission and the respective national professional organizations for chemistry, psychology, business, education, journalism, music, engineering, law, and medicine.
[src:northwestern-university/northwestern-university-p01] Northwestern conferred 2,190 bachelor's degrees, 3,272 master's degrees, 565 doctoral degrees, and 444 professional degrees in 2012–2013.
[src:northwestern-university/northwestern-university-p01] Since 1951, Northwestern has awarded 520 honorary degrees.
[src:northwestern-university/northwestern-university-p01] Northwestern also has chapters of academic honor societies such as Phi Beta Kappa (Alpha of Illinois), Eta Kappa Nu, Tau Beta Pi, Eta Sigma Phi (Beta chapter), Lambda Pi Eta, and Alpha Sigma Lambda (Alpha chapter).
[src:northwestern-university/northwestern-university-p01] Northwestern maintains a student-to-faculty ratio of 6:1.
[src:northwestern-university/northwestern-university-p01] 77% of the classes have less than 20 students while 5.5% of the classes have more than 50 students.
[src:northwestern-university/northwestern-university-p01] Northwestern Libraries host a total of 8,198,268 printed or electronic volumes.
[src:northwestern-university/northwestern-university-p01] In addition, its libraries contain 229,198 maps, 211,127 audio files, 103,377 printed journals, 196,716 electronic journals, 91,334 movies or videos, 36,989 manuscripts, 4.6 million microforms, and almost 99,000 periodicals.
[src:northwestern-university/northwestern-university-p01] The University Library is the 14th-largest university library in North America based on total number of titles held.
[src:northwestern-university/northwestern-university-p01] Northwestern, along with 15 other universities, participates in digitizing its collections as part of the Google Book Search project.
[src:northwestern-university/northwestern-university-p01] Northwestern was elected to the Association of American Universities in 1917 and is classified as an R1 university, denoting "very high" research activity.
[src:northwestern-university/northwestern-university-p01] Northwestern's schools of management, engineering, and communication are among the most academically productive in the nation.
[src:northwestern-university/northwestern-university-p01] The university received $923.8 million in research funding and $421 million in NIH funding in 2022 and houses over 90 school-based and 40 university-wide research institutes and centers.
[src:northwestern-university/northwestern-university-p01] Northwestern also supports nearly 1,500 research laboratories across two campuses, predominantly in the medical and biological sciences.
[src:northwestern-university/northwestern-university-p01] Also, Northwestern houses more than 50 University Research Institutes & Centers (URICS), which consists of institutes and initiatives that combine multiple areas of study to pursue research across domains such as quantum information, policy research, bioelectronics, and more.
[src:northwestern-university/northwestern-university-p01] The university also shares collaborative research efforts with other universities such as the CZ Biohub Chicago with the University of Chicago and University of Illinois.
[src:northwestern-university/northwestern-university-p01] In addition, Northwestern University cooperates with research institutions such as Argonne National Laboratory and Fermi National Accelerator Laboratory (FermiLab).
[src:northwestern-university/northwestern-university-p01] Proceeding in cooperation with these laboratories, the Center for Applied Physics and Superconducting Technologies (CAPST) and the Initiative at Northwestern for Quantum Information Research and Engineering (INQUIRE) have attracted attention in recent years.
[src:northwestern-university/northwestern-university-p01] Northwestern's investment and collaboration areas include particle physics, quantum physics, quantum information technologies, and superconducting technologies.
[src:northwestern-university/northwestern-university-p01] In 2013, Northwestern researchers disclosed 247 inventions, filed 270 patent applications, received 81 foreign and US patents, started 12 companies, and generated $79.8 million in licensing revenue.
[src:northwestern-university/northwestern-university-p01] The Innovation and New Ventures Office (INVO) has been involved in creating the Center for Developmental Therapeutics (CDT) and the Center for Device Development (CD2).
[src:northwestern-university/northwestern-university-p01] Northwestern files hundreds of patents each year, ranking among the top 20 universities in the world in terms of U.S. utility patents.
[src:northwestern-university/northwestern-university-p01] One of the university's most successful current patents is pregabalin, a synthesized organic molecule developed at the university by chemistry professor Richard Bruce Silverman (for whom Silverman Hall was named).
[src:northwestern-university/northwestern-university-p01] It was ultimately marketed as Lyrica, a drug sold by Pfizer, to combat epilepsy, neuropathic pain, and fibromyalgia.
[src:northwestern-university/northwestern-university-p01] Northwestern has an extensive history of producing prominent businessmen and entrepreneurs.
[src:northwestern-university/northwestern-university-p01] Companies founded by Northwestern alumni include Groupon, The Blackstone Group, Booz Allen Hamilton, U.S.
[src:northwestern-university/northwestern-university-p01] Steel, Kirkland & Ellis, Guggenheim Partners, Accenture, Aon Corporation, and AQR Capital.
[src:northwestern-university/northwestern-university-p01] The university also runs The Garage, and interdisciplinary innovation and entrepreneurship space and community for student-run startups.
[src:northwestern-university/northwestern-university-p01] The Garage provides students with resources and programming related to entrepreneurship and mentorship.
[src:northwestern-university/northwestern-university-p01] The Garage houses approximately 90 student-founded startups per academic quarter.
[src:northwestern-university/northwestern-university-p01] Its programs and resources are available to all Northwestern students.
[src:northwestern-university/northwestern-university-p01] Northwestern enrolls more than 8000 undergraduate students and more than 8000 graduate students each year, as mentioned on the "About Our Students: Recruit at Northwestern" page on Northwestern's website.
[src:northwestern-university/northwestern-university-p01] The freshman retention rate for that year was 99%.
[src:northwestern-university/northwestern-university-p01] Eighty-six percent of students graduated after four years and 96% graduated after six years.
[src:northwestern-university/northwestern-university-p01] The undergraduate population is drawn from all 50 states and over 75 foreign countries.
[src:northwestern-university/northwestern-university-p01] Twenty percent of students in the Class of 2024 were Pell Grant recipients and 12.56% were first-generation college students.
[src:northwestern-university/northwestern-university-p01] Northwestern also enrolls the ninth-most National Merit Scholars of any university in the nation.
[src:northwestern-university/northwestern-university-p01] The five most commonly awarded undergraduate degrees are economics, journalism, communication studies, psychology, and political science.
[src:northwestern-university/northwestern-university-p01] The Kellogg School of Management's MBA, the School of Law's JD, and the Feinberg School of Medicine's MD are the three largest professional degree programs by enrollment.
[src:northwestern-university/northwestern-university-p01] With 2,446 students enrolled in science, engineering, and health fields, the largest graduate programs by enrollment include chemistry, integrated biology, material sciences, electrical and computer engineering, neuroscience, and economics.
[src:northwestern-university/northwestern-university-p01] Northwestern offers both traditional residence halls and residential colleges for students who share a particular intellectual interest.
[src:northwestern-university/northwestern-university-p01] Residence halls include Allison Hall, Bobb-McCulloch, Elder Hall, Foster-Walker Complex (commonly referred to as Plex), Rogers House, and Shapiro Hall (formerly known as 560 Lincoln) among others.
[src:northwestern-university/northwestern-university-p01] An estimated 20% of undergraduates are affiliated with a fraternity or sorority.
[src:northwestern-university/northwestern-university-p01] Northwestern recognizes 21 fraternities and 18 sororities.
[src:northwestern-university/northwestern-university-p01] All incoming undergraduates at Northwestern University are required to live on campus for their first two years.
[src:northwestern-university/northwestern-university-p01] One of Northwestern's student charity events is Dance Marathon.
[src:northwestern-university/northwestern-university-p01] It has raised over $1 million for charity every year since 2011 and has donated a total of $13 million to children's charities since its conception.
[src:northwestern-university/northwestern-university-p01] The Northwestern Community Development Corps (NCDC) is a student-run organization that connects hundreds of student volunteers to community development projects in Evanston and Chicago throughout the year.
[src:northwestern-university/northwestern-university-p01] The group also holds a number of annual community events, including Project Pumpkin, a Halloween celebration that provides over 800 local children with carnival events and a safe venue to trick-or-treat each year.
[src:northwestern-university/northwestern-university-p01] Several international nongovernmental organizations were established at Northwestern, including the World Health Imaging, Informatics and Telemedicine Alliance, a spin-off from an engineering student's honors thesis.
[src:northwestern-university/northwestern-university-p01] Northwestern is a prolific producer of successful entertainers and a nationally reputed hub for collegiate performing arts.
[src:northwestern-university/northwestern-university-p01] The Student Theatre Coalition, or StuCo, organizes nine student theater companies, multiple performance groups, and over sixty independent productions each year.
[src:northwestern-university/northwestern-university-p01] Productions include The Waa-Mu Show, an original musical written and produced entirely by students, and the Dolphin show.
[src:northwestern-university/northwestern-university-p01] Children's theater is represented on campus by Griffin's Tale and Purple Crayon Players.
[src:northwestern-university/northwestern-university-p01] Chicago's Lookingglass Theatre Company, which began life in Jones Residential College, was founded in 1988 by several university alumni, including David Schwimmer.
[src:northwestern-university/northwestern-university-p01] It received the Regional Tony Award in 2011 and has won over 45 Joseph Jefferson Awards in its 30 seasons.
[src:northwestern-university/northwestern-university-p01] The undergraduate students maintain twelve a cappella groups, including THUNK a cappella, the Northwestern Undertones, Freshman Fifteen A Cappella, ShireiNU A Cappella, and Purple Haze.
[src:northwestern-university/northwestern-university-p01] Northwestern's performing arts scene also includes Boomshaka, which is the university's drum, dance, and rhythm ensemble.
[src:northwestern-university/northwestern-university-p01] The Northwestern Debate Society has won fifteen National Debate Tournaments, the highest number of any university.
[src:northwestern-university/northwestern-university-p01] Alumni of the society include Erwin Chemerinsky, legal scholar and Dean of UC Berkeley School of Law, and Elliot Mincberg of People For the American Way.
[src:northwestern-university/northwestern-university-p01] Northwestern's Mock Trial team had two teams qualify for the 2018 National Championship Tournament hosted by the American Mock Trial Association, making Northwestern one of seven schools in the nation to be represented by multiple teams at the competition.
[src:northwestern-university/northwestern-university-p01] One of the two teams finished 9th in their division and is ranked 20th in the country out of roughly 750 teams for the 2018–2019 season.
[src:northwestern-university/northwestern-university-p02] Northwestern is a charter member of the Big Ten Conference.
[src:northwestern-university/northwestern-university-p02] It was the conference's only private university until 2024's addition of USC and possesses by far the smallest undergraduate enrollment (the next-smallest member, the University of Iowa, is roughly three times as large, with almost 22,000 undergraduates).
[src:northwestern-university/northwestern-university-p02] Northwestern fields 19 intercollegiate athletic teams (8 men's and 11 women's) in addition to numerous club sports.
[src:northwestern-university/northwestern-university-p02] Twelve of Northwestern's varsity programs have had NCAA or bowl postseason appearances.
[src:northwestern-university/northwestern-university-p02] Northwestern is one of five private AAU members to compete in NCAA Power Five conferences (the other four are Duke, Stanford, USC, and Vanderbilt) and maintains a 98% NCAA Graduation Success Rate, the highest among Football Bowl Subdivision schools.
[src:northwestern-university/northwestern-university-p02] In 2018, the school opened the Walter Athletics Center, a $270 million state-of-the-art lakefront facility for its athletics teams.
[src:northwestern-university/northwestern-university-p02] In 1972, the student body voted to change the official nickname to "Purple Haze," but the new name never stuck.
[src:northwestern-university/northwestern-university-p02] The mascot of Northwestern Athletics is Willie the Wildcat.
[src:northwestern-university/northwestern-university-p02] Prior to Willie, the team mascot had been a live, caged bear cub from the Lincoln Park Zoo named Furpaw, who was brought to the playing field on game days to greet the fans.
[src:northwestern-university/northwestern-university-p02] After a losing season, the team decided that Furpaw was to blame for its misfortune and decided to select a new mascot.
[src:northwestern-university/northwestern-university-p02] Willie the Wildcat made his debut in 1933, first as a logo and then in three dimensions in 1947, when members of the Alpha Delta fraternity dressed as wildcats during a Homecoming Parade.
[src:northwestern-university/northwestern-university-p02] The Northwestern Wildcats football team is a Division I college football team and member of the Big Ten Conference.
[src:northwestern-university/northwestern-university-p02] The team has a history dating back to 1882.
[src:northwestern-university/northwestern-university-p02] The team has achieved success, winning three Big Ten championships or co-championships since 1995.
[src:northwestern-university/northwestern-university-p02] Additionally, they have been eligible to participate in bowl games five times between 2015 and 2020.
[src:northwestern-university/northwestern-university-p02] Northwestern takes pride in its academic achievements as well, consistently ranking among the top football teams in graduation rates.
[src:northwestern-university/northwestern-university-p02] They have been honored with the AFCA Academic Achievement Award four times since 2002.
[src:northwestern-university/northwestern-university-p02] The Wildcats play their home games at Ryan Field, a new stadium on the site of the original Ryan Field.
[src:northwestern-university/northwestern-university-p02] Northwestern's football team has made 73 appearances in the top 10 of the AP poll since 1936 (including five at #1) and has won eight Big Ten conference championships since 1903.
[src:northwestern-university/northwestern-university-p02] At one time, Northwestern had the longest losing streak in Division I-A, losing 34 consecutive games between 1979 and 1982.
[src:northwestern-university/northwestern-university-p02] They did not appear in a bowl game after 1949 until the 1996 Rose Bowl.
[src:northwestern-university/northwestern-university-p02] The team did not win a bowl since the 1949 Rose Bowl until the 2013 Gator Bowl.
[src:northwestern-university/northwestern-university-p02] Following the sudden death of football coach Randy Walker in 2006, 31-year-old former All-American Northwestern linebacker Pat Fitzgerald assumed the position, becoming the youngest Division I FBS coach at the time.
[src:northwestern-university/northwestern-university-p02] In 1882 as a group of Northwestern men played a "football heat" against a group of Lake Forest men.
[src:northwestern-university/northwestern-university-p02] The Wildcats have since achieved an all-time-high rank of No.
[src:northwestern-university/northwestern-university-p02] 1 during the 1936 and 1962 seasons, which has thus far not been duplicated.
[src:northwestern-university/northwestern-university-p02] The team plays home games at Ryan Field in Evanston, Illinois.
[src:northwestern-university/northwestern-university-p02] The Wildcats have participated in a total of 16 bowl games, including appearances in 10 seasons between 2008 and 2020.
[src:northwestern-university/northwestern-university-p02] During the 2016–2018 seasons, they won three consecutive bowl games.
[src:northwestern-university/northwestern-university-p02] In 2020, the Wildcats claimed the title of Big Ten West Champions and were champions in their bowl game.
[src:northwestern-university/northwestern-university-p02] The Helms Athletic Foundation named the men's basketball team the 1931 National Champion.
[src:northwestern-university/northwestern-university-p02] In 2017, the men's basketball team earned an NCAA berth for the first time in the program's history.
[src:northwestern-university/northwestern-university-p02] They won their first-round matchup against Vanderbilt University but lost to number-one seed Gonzaga in the second round.
[src:northwestern-university/northwestern-university-p02] In 1998, two former Northwestern basketball players were charged and convicted for sports bribery, having been paid to shave points in games against three other Big Ten schools during the 1995 season.
[src:northwestern-university/northwestern-university-p02] The football team became embroiled in a different betting scandal later that year when federal prosecutors indicted four former players for perjury related to betting on their own games.
[src:northwestern-university/northwestern-university-p02] In August 2001, Rashidi Wheeler, a senior safety, collapsed and died during practice from an asthma attack.
[src:northwestern-university/northwestern-university-p02] An autopsy revealed that he had ephedrine, a stimulant banned by the NCAA, in his system, which prompted Northwestern to investigate the prevalence of stimulants and other banned substances across all of its athletic programs.
[src:northwestern-university/northwestern-university-p02] In 2006, the Northwestern women's soccer team was suspended and coach Jenny Haigh resigned following the release of images of alleged hazing.
[src:northwestern-university/northwestern-university-p02] The Wildcats men's basketball team is under the direction of Sullivan-Ubben head men's basketball coach Chris Collins, a role that he has been in since 2013.
[src:northwestern-university/northwestern-university-p02] Collins led the Wildcats to heights never before reached during the 2016–17 season when the program saw a school-record 24 wins and its first NCAA tournament berth and victory in program history.
[src:northwestern-university/northwestern-university-p02] Collins was named as one of four finalists for the Naismith Men's Coach of the Year award in 2017.
[src:northwestern-university/northwestern-university-p02] Northwestern’s 1930–31 team was retroactively named national champion by both the Helms Athletic Foundation and the Premo-Porretta Power Poll.
[src:northwestern-university/northwestern-university-p02] Since then, the Wildcats have played in the National Invitation Tournament seven times, most recently in 2012.
[src:northwestern-university/northwestern-university-p02] The men's basketball program was the first to open the renovated Welsh-Ryan Arena on November 2, 2018, in an exhibition game against McKendree.
[src:northwestern-university/northwestern-university-p02] The facility was built to be the most accessible arena in college athletics and seats 7,039.
[src:northwestern-university/northwestern-university-p02] In 2017, the Wildcats saw its highest draft pick in program history with Nia Coffey, selected fifth overall by the San Antonio Stars.
[src:northwestern-university/northwestern-university-p02] The first player drafted in program history was Amy Jaeschke in 2011, selected 27th overall by the Chicago Sky.
[src:northwestern-university/northwestern-university-p02] The Northwestern Fencing program competes in the Central Collegiate Conference and has a tenured history of success.
[src:northwestern-university/northwestern-university-p02] Zach Moss is the programs head coach, a role that he has been in since 2016.
[src:northwestern-university/northwestern-university-p02] Following a historic 2017–18 season, Moss was named the Midwest Fencing Conference Coach of the Year as the Wildcats captured their fifth-ever conference championship and finished with three All-Americans at the NCAA Championships.
[src:northwestern-university/northwestern-university-p02] Additionally, the team set the program record for most wins in a season with 47 and the program record for longest win streak at 25.
[src:northwestern-university/northwestern-university-p02] The 2018–19 season saw more milestones for the Wildcats including a 39–5 record, an 11th-place finish at the NCAA Championships, and a second consecutive conference championship.
[src:northwestern-university/northwestern-university-p02] The Wildcats achieved the highest ranking in program history during the season at second in the country and amassed 39 victories at the conference championships.
[src:northwestern-university/northwestern-university-p02] The Northwestern Field Hockey team plays its home games at Lakeside Field, adjacent to Lanny and Sharon Martin Stadium on the lakefront.
[src:northwestern-university/northwestern-university-p02] The Wildcats are led by head coach Tracey Fuchs, a role that she has been in since 2009.
[src:northwestern-university/northwestern-university-p02] Fuchs has led the Wildcats to two Big Ten titles and three NCAA tournament appearances.
[src:northwestern-university/northwestern-university-p02] Under Fuchs' direction, the Wildcats have posted winning seasons in 10 of her 11 seasons.
[src:northwestern-university/northwestern-university-p02] The Northwestern Wildcats field hockey team has gathered six regular-season Big Ten titles and 1 tournament title in addition to 14 NCAA tournament appearances.
[src:northwestern-university/northwestern-university-p02] In 2021, the team won the NCAA tournament, followed by a championship game appearance in 2022.
[src:northwestern-university/northwestern-university-p02] Northwestern lacrosse has won the national championship in women's lacrosse five straight times, from 2005 to 2009, and then again in 2011 and 2012, giving them seven championships in eight years.
[src:northwestern-university/northwestern-university-p02] In 2007, the team joined Maryland as the only other school to three-peat.
[src:northwestern-university/northwestern-university-p02] The run started in 2005, when the team enjoyed a perfect season and defeated many long-established east-coast schools after only five years as a varsity sport to capture the school's first national championship since 1941.
[src:northwestern-university/northwestern-university-p02] In doing so, it became the westernmost institution to ever win the title.
[src:northwestern-university/northwestern-university-p02] Soon after, the team made national news when members appeared in a White House photo with President Bush wearing thong sandals, or flip-flops, dubbed as the "White House flip-flop flap." The 2009 season also was an undefeated run.
[src:northwestern-university/northwestern-university-p02] In their five consecutive championship seasons, the Wildcats have a 106–3 record.
[src:northwestern-university/northwestern-university-p02] The Wildcats are led by head coach Kelly Amonte-Hiller, a role that she has been in since 2002.
[src:northwestern-university/northwestern-university-p02] The Wildcats won their first-ever Big Ten Championship in 2019 and won their first-ever Big Ten regular season championship in 2021.
[src:northwestern-university/northwestern-university-p02] Most recently, Northwestern won its ninth NCAA championship in 2026, after having won in 2023 and was runner-up 2024 and 2025.
[src:northwestern-university/northwestern-university-p02] The Northwestern Wildcats wrestling program hosts home matches in Welsh-Ryan Arena and practices in the Ken Kraft Wrestling Room, located in Anderson Hall.
[src:northwestern-university/northwestern-university-p02] The Wildcats are led by Matt Storniolo, a role that he has been in since 2016.
[src:northwestern-university/northwestern-university-p02] The Wildcats have had 40 Big Ten individual champions in addition to 10 NCAA individual champions and 75-plus All-Americans.
[src:northwestern-university/northwestern-university-p02] They have twice placed second in the NCAA Championships: 1939, 1945.
[src:northwestern-university/northwestern-university-p02] Luke Donald won the NCAA Individual Championship in 1999.
[src:northwestern-university/northwestern-university-p02] He was Big Ten Conference Player of the year in 1999, and David Merkow was named the same in 2006.
[src:northwestern-university/northwestern-university-p02] Donald was ranked number 1 in the Official World Golf Ranking for 56 weeks in 2011 and 2012.
[src:northwestern-university/northwestern-university-p02] Northwestern's political alumni include U.S.
[src:northwestern-university/northwestern-university-p02] Senator and presidential candidate George McGovern and Chicago Mayor Rahm Emanuel.
[src:northwestern-university/northwestern-university-p02] Law school graduates include orator William Jennings Bryan, U.S.
[src:northwestern-university/northwestern-university-p02] Supreme Court Associate Justice John Paul Stevens, Supreme Court Justice and United Nations Ambassador Arthur Joseph Goldberg, Chicago Mayor Harold L.
[src:northwestern-university/northwestern-university-p02] Washington, Governor of Illinois and Democratic presidential candidate Adlai Stevenson, prominent American civil rights attorney, Howard University President, and United Nations Ambassador James Nabrit Jr.**,** and Cincinnati mayor and tabloid host Jerry Springer.
[src:northwestern-university/northwestern-university-p02] Other media alumni include Stephen Colbert and Seth Meyers.
[src:northwestern-university/northwestern-university-p02] Others include Nobel Prize-winning economists George J.
[src:northwestern-university/northwestern-university-p02] Stigler and Peter Howitt, Nobel Prize-winning novelist Saul Bellow, and Nobel Prize winning biochemist Robert F.
[src:northwestern-university/northwestern-university-p02] Pulitzer Prize-winning composer and diarist Ned Rorem, *A Song of Ice and Fire* author George R.
[src:northwestern-university/northwestern-university-p02] Martin, Pulitzer Prize-winning composer Howard Hanson, historian and novelist Wilma Dykeman, and National Prayer Breakfast founder Abraham Vereide are also among its alumni.
[src:northwestern-university/northwestern-university-p02] Among U.S. universities, Northwestern ranks eighth in the number of billionaires produced.
[src:northwestern-university/northwestern-university-p02] Northwestern alumni have founded companies and organizations including the Mayo Clinic, The Blackstone Group, U.S.
[src:northwestern-university/northwestern-university-p02] Steel, Accenture, Aon Corporation, and Booz Allen Hamilton.
[src:northwestern-university/northwestern-university-p02] The university employs 3,781 faculty members across its eleven schools, including 18 members of the National Academy of Sciences, 65 members of the American Academy of Arts and Sciences, 19 members of the National Academy of Engineering, and 6 members of the Institute of Medicine.
[src:northwestern-university/northwestern-university-p02] Faculty include 2010 Nobel laureate in Economics Dale T.
[src:northwestern-university/northwestern-university-p02] Mortensen; 2025 Nobel laureate in Economics Joel Mokyr; nano-scientists Chad Mirkin and Samuel I.
[src:northwestern-university/northwestern-university-p02] Rogers, Mark Hersam, William Dichtel, and Dylan Penningroth.
[src:northwestern-university/northwestern-university-p02] The faculty also includes Holocaust denier Arthur Butz and Richard Bruce Silverman, inventor of Lyrica (Pregabalin).
[src:northwestern-university/northwestern-university-p02] Former faculty include political advisor David Axelrod, artists William Conger, Judy Ledgerwood, Ed Paschke, and James Valerio, writer Charles Newman, Nobel Prize–winning chemist John Pople, and military sociologist and "don't ask, don't tell" author Charles Moskos.
